Verstappen's first experience in a racing car was at the [[Pembrey Circuit]] on 11 October 2013. He drove 160 laps in a [[Barazi-Epsilon]] FR2.0–10 [[Formula Renault]] car. The car was provided by Dutch team [[MP Motorsport]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Max Verstappen sensationeel in allereerste meters Formule Renault 2.0|url=http://www.racexpress.nl/formule-1/max-verstappen-sensationeel-in-allereerste-meters-formule-renault-2-0/n/53111|work=RaceXpress.nl|access-date=27 January 2014|archive-date=5 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205021915/http://www.racexpress.nl/formule-1/max-verstappen-sensationeel-in-allereerste-meters-formule-renault-2-0/n/53111|url-status=live}}</ref> He tested for several Formula Renault 2.0 teams in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gpupdate.net/nl/autosport-nieuws/303024/verstappen-max-al-net-zo-snel-als-ervaren-coureurs/|title=Verstappen: "Max al net zo snel als ervaren coureurs"|website=GPUpdate.net|access-date=2 September 2017|archive-date=2 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170902224144/http://www.gpupdate.net/nl/autosport-nieuws/303024/verstappen-max-al-net-zo-snel-als-ervaren-coureurs/|url-status=live}}</ref> In December 2013, Verstappen tested a [[Dallara]] F311 [[Formula Three|Formula 3]] car run by [[Motopark Academy]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Max Verstappen flies in Formula 3 test debut|url=https://www.autosport.com/fia-f3/news/max-verstappen-flies-in-formula-3-test-debut-4471773/4471773/|access-date=20 January 2022|website=[[Autosport]]|archive-date=20 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220120130449/https://www.autosport.com/fia-f3/news/max-verstappen-flies-in-formula-3-test-debut-4471773/4471773/|url-status=live}}</ref> An additional Formula Renault test followed in December at [[Circuito de Jerez]]. Driving for [[Josef Kaufmann Racing]], Verstappen went faster than Formula Renault regulars like [[Steijn Schothorst]] and [[Matt Parry]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Max op haar na snelste bij laatste FR 2.0 test van 2013|url=http://www.verstappen.nl/?locatie=bericht&id=8323|work=Verstappen Info Page|access-date=27 January 2014|archive-date=5 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205012246/http://www.verstappen.nl/?locatie=bericht&id=8323|url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[Circuit Ricardo Tormo]] near [[Valencia]], Verstappen set a faster lap time than the more experienced driver [[Eddie Cheever III]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Max fenomenaal snel bij zijn eerste F3 test op Valencia|url=http://www.verstappen.nl/?locatie=bericht&id=8326|work=Verstappen Info Page|access-date=27 January 2014|archive-date=5 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205012216/http://www.verstappen.nl/?locatie=bericht&id=8326|url-status=live}}</ref>

==== 2014: Florida Winter Series and Formula Three ====
On 16 January 2014, it was announced Verstappen would make his racing debut in the non-championship [[Florida Winter Series]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Max maakt autosportdebuut in Florida Winter Series|url=http://www.verstappen.nl/?locatie=bericht&id=8336|work=Verstappen Info Page|access-date=27 January 2014|archive-date=5 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205012639/http://www.verstappen.nl/?locatie=bericht&id=8336|url-status=live}}</ref> On 5 February, at the second race weekend, Verstappen won the race at [[Palm Beach International Raceway]] after he started from pole.<ref>{{cite web|title=Verstappen wint eerste autorace na regen en rode vlag|url=http://www.gpupdate.net/nl/autosport-nieuws/306301/verstappen-wint-eerste-autorace-na-rode-vlag|access-date=16 May 2016|archive-date=6 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306004252/http://www.gpupdate.net/nl/autosport-nieuws/306301/verstappen-wint-eerste-autorace-na-rode-vlag/|url-status=live}}</ref> A few weeks later, Verstappen won his second race of the series at [[Homestead–Miami Speedway]] after beating [[Nicholas Latifi]] by 0.004 seconds.<ref>{{Citation|title=Max Verstappen Onboard FWS, Homestead race 3, 19/02/2014 – Max beats Latifi by 0.004s!| date=11 March 2014 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rJQHa6nHV04|access-date=20 January 2022|archive-date=13 October 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221013203425/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rJQHa6nHV04|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Formule 1 nieuws – Lees het laatste nieuws over Formule 1|url=https://nl.motorsport.com/f1/news/|access-date=20 January 2022|website=nl.motorsport.com|language=nl|archive-date=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318043055/https://www.autosport.com/|url-status=live}}</ref>

Following his single-seater debut in the inaugural Florida Winter Series, Verstappen drove in the [[2014 FIA Formula 3 European Championship]] for [[Van Amersfoort Racing]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fiaf3europe.com/en/news/Max-Verstappen-new-Red-Bull-Junior.html |title=Max Verstappen new part of the Red Bull Junior Team |publisher=Fédération Internationale de l'Automobile |access-date=20 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924012244/http://www.fiaf3europe.com/en/news/Max-Verstappen-new-Red-Bull-Junior.html |archive-date=24 September 2015}}</ref> Aged 16, Verstappen achieved 10 victories in total—including a record six consecutive wins at [[Spa-Francorchamps]] and the [[Norisring]]—along with eight retirements and one missed start, becoming the youngest race winner and polesitter in [[Formula Three]] history at the [[Hockenheimring]]; he placed third in the overall standings, with the most wins.<ref>{{cite web|title=Max Verstappen|url=https://www.redbull.com/gb-en/athlete/max-verstappen-bio|access-date=29 January 2022|publisher=Red Bull |archive-date=29 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220129030707/https://www.redbull.com/gb-en/athlete/max-verstappen-bio|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=2014 European F3 Championship|url=https://www.motorsportmagazine.com/database/championships/2014-european-f3-championship/|access-date=19 January 2022|work=Motor Sport Magazine|archive-date=22 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220122204809/https://www.motorsportmagazine.com/database/championships/2014-european-f3-championship/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Max Verstappen: what I learned in F3|date=2 August 2016 |url=https://www.redbull.com/gb-en/max-verstappen-interview-european-f3-review-2014|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Red Bull|archive-date=22 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220122204809/https://www.redbull.com/gb-en/max-verstappen-interview-european-f3-review-2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.autosport.com/fia-f3/news/hockenheim-european-f3-max-verstappen-takes-maiden-f3-win-4471969/4471969/|title=Hockenheim European F3: Max Verstappen takes maiden F3 win|date=4 May 2014|access-date=28 November 2024|website=[[Autosport]]|first=Marcus|last=Simmons|archive-date=3 December 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241203010943/https://www.autosport.com/fia-f3/news/hockenheim-european-f3-max-verstappen-takes-maiden-f3-win-4471969/4471969/|url-status=live}}</ref>

== Formula One career ==

During the first practice session at the [[2014 Japanese Grand Prix]], Verstappen replaced [[Jean-Éric Vergne]] as part of his preparation for a full-time seat at [[Scuderia Toro Rosso|Toro Rosso]] in the {{f1|2015}} season.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Benson|first=Andrew|date=29 September 2014|title=Max Verstappen: Teenager to drive in practice at Japanese Grand Prix|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/formula1/29408212|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160601084502/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/formula1/29408212|archive-date=1 June 2016|access-date=23 July 2016|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref> Aged 17 years and three days, Verstappen was the youngest person in history to participate in a Formula One race weekend.<ref>{{Cite web |date=24 July 2016 |title=Japanese Grand Prix 2014: History-maker Max Verstappen flies like the wind as typhoon zooms closer |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/motor-racing/japanese-grand-prix-2014-history-maker-max-verstappen-flies-like-the-wind-as-typhoon-zooms-closer-9773924.html |access-date=22 January 2022 |website=[[The Independent]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160724110219/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/motor-racing/japanese-grand-prix-2014-history-maker-max-verstappen-flies-like-the-wind-as-typhoon-zooms-closer-9773924.html |archive-date=24 July 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref> In August 2014, Verstappen joined the [[Red Bull Junior Team]] after testing a Formula Renault 3.5 car. He also considered an offer from [[Mercedes-Benz in Formula One|Mercedes]] to join their [[Mercedes Junior Team|driver development programme]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nu.nl/sport/3850611/max-verstappen-per-direct-opgenomen-in-opleiding-red-bull.html|title=Max Verstappen per direct opgenomen in opleiding Red Bull|date=12 August 2014|work=verstappen.nl |access-date=18 August 2014|publisher=Nu.nl|archive-date=22 May 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210522154400/https://www.nu.nl/sport/3850611/max-verstappen-per-direct-opgenomen-in-opleiding-red-bull.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Toro Rosso (2015–2016) ===
[[File:Max Verstappen 2015 Malaysia Q2.jpg|thumb|Verstappen (pictured at the [[2015 Malaysian Grand Prix]]) became the youngest driver in Formula One history at the {{F1GP|2015|Australian}}, aged 17.]]
Verstappen became the [[List of Formula One driver records#Youngest drivers to start a race|youngest driver to start a World Championship race]] through joining Toro Rosso's race drivers' line-up with [[Carlos Sainz Jr.|Carlos Sainz]] as his teammate, in his Grand Prix debut as a full-time driver at the [[2015 Australian Grand Prix]] at the age of {{Age in years and days|1997|9|30|2015|3|15}}{{Emdash}}breaking [[Jaime Alguersuari]]'s existing record by almost two years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Max Verstappen to race with Toro Rosso F1 team in 2015|website=Autosport|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/115435|date=18 August 2014|access-date=18 August 2014|archive-date=1 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701130917/http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/115435|url-status=live}}</ref> In this first race, Verstappen ran in points-scoring positions until he was forced to retire due to an engine failure.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/118069|title=Lewis Hamilton beats Nico Rosberg to win|first=Lawrence|last=Barretto|website=Autosport|date=15 March 2015|access-date=29 March 2015|archive-date=16 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150316231343/http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/118069|url-status=live}}</ref> However, at the subsequent race in [[2015 Malaysian Grand Prix|Malaysia]], Verstappen qualified sixth and finished the race in seventh place, scoring his first Formula One points aged {{Age in years and days|1997|9|30|2015|3|29}}, breaking the record of the then-[[List of Formula One driver records#Youngest drivers to score points|youngest driver to score World Championship points]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/motorsport/formulaone/sebastian-vettel/11502398/Malaysian-GP-2015-Sebastian-Vettel-picks-up-surprise-win-for-Ferrari-to-blow-world-title-wide-open.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/motorsport/formulaone/sebastian-vettel/11502398/Malaysian-GP-2015-Sebastian-Vettel-picks-up-surprise-win-for-Ferrari-to-blow-world-title-wide-open.html |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|title=Sebastian Vettel picks up surprise win for Ferrari to blow world title wide open|first=Daniel|last=Johnson|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=29 March 2015|access-date=29 March 2015|quote=Max Verstappen took seventh to become the youngest points scorer in F1 history, at 17 years and 180 days.}}{{cbignore}}</ref>

At the [[2015 Monaco Grand Prix]], Verstappen was involved in a high-speed collision with [[Romain Grosjean]], after clipping the back of Grosjean's [[Lotus F1|Lotus]] on the approach to the tight first corner, Sainte Devote, and crashed into the barriers at high speed.<ref>{{Citation|title=5 Crazy Onboards {{!}} Monaco Grand Prix| date=22 May 2018 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sMde0gU-KhQ|access-date=20 January 2022|archive-date=20 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220120132014/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sMde0gU-KhQ|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Monaco GP: Max Verstappen penalised for crash with Romain Grosjean|url=https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/monaco-gp-max-verstappen-penalised-for-crash-with-romain-grosjean-5006608/5006608/|access-date=20 January 2022|website=Autosport|date=24 May 2015 |archive-date=17 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211217052426/https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/monaco-gp-max-verstappen-penalised-for-crash-with-romain-grosjean-5006608/5006608/|url-status=live}}</ref> Verstappen was given a five-place grid penalty for causing the accident, and was branded "dangerous" by [[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]] driver [[Felipe Massa]].<ref>William Esler, "[http://www.skysports.com/f1/news/31381/9875227/max-verstappen-hits-back-at-felipe-massa-of-monaco-crash-criticism Max Verstappen hits back at Felipe Massa over Monaco crash criticism] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611182531/http://www.skysports.com/f1/news/31381/9875227/max-verstappen-hits-back-at-felipe-massa-of-monaco-crash-criticism |date=11 June 2016}}", [[Sky Sports]], 2015.</ref>

Verstappen continued to regularly finish in the points as well as achieving his best finish of the 2015 season in [[2015 Hungarian Grand Prix|Hungary]] by finishing fourth,<ref>{{Cite web|title=9 things we learned from the Hungarian Grand Prix|date=26 July 2015 |url=https://www.redbull.com/gb-en/2015-hungarian-grand-prix-f1-report|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Red Bull|archive-date=10 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220310191111/https://www.redbull.com/gb-en/2015-hungarian-grand-prix-f1-report|url-status=live}}</ref> and equalled this result at the [[2015 United States Grand Prix|United States Grand Prix]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Hamilton seals 2015 title with thrilling Austin win|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/headlines/2015/10/hamilton-seals-2015-title-with-thrilling-austin-win.html|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=25 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211225175054/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/headlines/2015/10/hamilton-seals-2015-title-with-thrilling-austin-win.html|url-status=live}}</ref> At the end of the season, Verstappen received three awards at the [[FIA Prize Giving Ceremony]], for "Rookie of the Year", "Personality of the Year" and "Action of the Year", for his overtake on [[Felipe Nasr]] on the outside of the Blanchimont corner at the [[2015 Belgian Grand Prix|Belgian Grand Prix]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Galloway|first1=James|title=Lewis Hamilton & Mercedes officially crowned 2015 world champions|url=http://www.skysports.com/f1/news/24181/10087594/lewis-hamilton-mercedes-officially-crowned-2015-world-champions|publisher=Sky Sports|access-date=5 December 2015|date=5 December 2015|archive-date=5 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151205171818/http://www.skysports.com/f1/news/24181/10087594/lewis-hamilton-mercedes-officially-crowned-2015-world-champions|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Top 10 Moments of Max Verstappen Magic in F1| date=8 January 2020 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B4pF4bMwYYI|access-date=19 January 2022|archive-date=19 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220119223659/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B4pF4bMwYYI|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[File:Verstappen Bahrain 2016.jpg|alt=|thumb|Verstappen at the [[2016 Bahrain Grand Prix]]]]
Verstappen began the 2016 season at Toro Rosso, again alongside Sainz.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Max Verstappen and Carlos Sainz to continue for Toro Rosso in 2016|url=https://www.skysports.com/f1/news/12471/10084883/toro-rosso-have-confirmed-that-max-verstappen-and-carlos-sainz-will-race-in-2016|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Sky Sports|archive-date=19 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220119221049/https://www.skysports.com/f1/news/12471/10084883/toro-rosso-have-confirmed-that-max-verstappen-and-carlos-sainz-will-race-in-2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Verstappen qualified fifth for the opening race of the season in [[2016 Australian Grand Prix|Australia]], but during the race made several radio calls to his team due to frustration at being behind Sainz on track before Verstappen's Toro Rosso came into contact with his teammate's car whilst attempting to pass him with three laps to go, and he eventually finished tenth.<ref>"[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/formula1/35854819 Max Verstappen: Australian GP shows moody side of Toro Rosso teenager] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160323010100/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/formula1/35854819 |date=23 March 2016}}", BBC Sport, 2016.</ref> Verstappen enjoyed a more successful weekend at the following race in [[2016 Bahrain Grand Prix|Bahrain]], finishing sixth to score Toro Rosso's first-ever points at the Sakhir circuit.<ref>"[http://www.gpupdate.net/en/f1-news/337624/verstappen-scores-str-s-first-bahrain-points/ Verstappen scores STR's first Bahrain points] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511232826/http://www.gpupdate.net/en/f1-news/337624/verstappen-scores-str-s-first-bahrain-points/ |date=11 May 2016}}", ''GP Update'', 2016.</ref>

===Red Bull (2016–present)===
====2016: Youngest Grand Prix winner====
[[File:Verstappen Spain 2016.jpg|thumb|Verstappen celebrating victory at the [[2016 Spanish Grand Prix]], in his first race for the Red Bull Racing team]]

On 5 May 2016, following the {{F1GP|2016|Russian}}, Red Bull Racing announced that Verstappen would be replacing Daniil Kvyat from the [[2016 Spanish Grand Prix|Spanish Grand Prix]] onwards, with Kvyat returning to Toro Rosso.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Red Bull replace Kvyat with Verstappen|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/headlines/2016/5/red-bull-replace-kvyat-with-verstappen.html|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=20 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220120221159/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/headlines/2016/5/red-bull-replace-kvyat-with-verstappen.html|url-status=live}}</ref> According to Red Bull Team Principal [[Christian Horner]], "Max has proven to be an outstanding young talent. His performance at Toro Rosso has been impressive so far and we are pleased to give him the opportunity to drive for Red Bull Racing."<ref name="RBR Swap">{{cite news|url=http://www.redbullracing.com/article/new-line-spain|title=New line-up for Spain|work=RedBullRacing.com|date=5 May 2016|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508080016/http://www.redbullracing.com/article/new-line-spain|archive-date=8 May 2016}}</ref> After qualifying fourth for the Spanish Grand Prix,<ref name="Verstappen 4th in Qualifying">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/live/formula1/35946953|title=Hamilton takes pole in Spain|publisher=BBC Sport|date=14 May 2016|access-date=12 February 2018|archive-date=20 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181220042109/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/live/formula1/35946953|url-status=live}}</ref> Verstappen rose to second behind teammate [[Daniel Ricciardo]] on the opening lap after Mercedes teammates [[Lewis Hamilton]] and [[Nico Rosberg]] crashed out of the race.<ref>{{Cite web|title=WATCH: Mercedes collision puts Hamilton and Rosberg out on lap 1|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/headlines/2016/5/mercedes-collision-puts-hamilton-and-rosberg-out-on-lap-one.html|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=24 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220124222604/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/headlines/2016/5/mercedes-collision-puts-hamilton-and-rosberg-out-on-lap-one.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Verstappen took the race lead as he was placed on a two-stop rather than the same three-stop strategy as Ricciardo, and he held off [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]'s [[Kimi Räikkönen]] in the later stages of the race to take his first Formula One victory.<ref>{{Citation|title=2016 Spanish Grand Prix: Race Highlights| date=7 May 2017 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3B3-C914d_c|access-date=19 January 2022|archive-date=21 April 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220421042514/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3B3-C914d_c|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Verstappen's Maiden Win {{!}} Spanish Grand Prix 2016| date=28 January 2017 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hohuswdeznA|access-date=21 January 2022|archive-date=13 October 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221013203403/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hohuswdeznA|url-status=live}}</ref> By doing so he displaced [[Sebastian Vettel]] as the youngest driver ever to win a Formula One Grand Prix at the age of 18 years and 228 days.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/live/2016/may/15/f1-spanish-gp-live-lewis-hamilton-nico-rosberg|title=F1: Max Verstappen wins Spanish GP after Lewis Hamilton and Nico Rosberg crash – live!|last=Ostlere|first=Lawrence|date=15 May 2016|website=The Guardian|access-date=15 May 2016|archive-date=15 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515143832/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/live/2016/may/15/f1-spanish-gp-live-lewis-hamilton-nico-rosberg|url-status=live}}</ref>

In his first eight races with Red Bull, he achieved six top-five finishes, including four podiums.<ref name="Standings">{{cite web|url=https://www.statsf1.com/en/max-verstappen/grand-prix.aspx|title=Max Verstappen – Grands Prix|access-date=13 June 2022|website=StatsF1|archive-date=13 June 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220613195714/https://www.statsf1.com/en/max-verstappen/grand-prix.aspx|url-status=live}}</ref>

During the [[2016 Belgian Grand Prix|Belgian Grand Prix]], Verstappen collided with Räikkönen at the first corner, pushed Vettel, Räikkönen and Pérez wide at ''Les Combes'', and aggressively blocked Räikkönen on the Kemmel straight.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/formula1/37226080|title=Formula 1: Max Verstappen gets under the skin of top drivers|publisher=BBC Sport|date=31 August 2016|access-date=4 November 2016|archive-date=13 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161113170546/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/formula1/37226080|url-status=live}}</ref> Verstappen was criticised for his driving, with Räikkönen saying that he was "going to cause a huge accident sooner or later." Christian Horner noted that the driving was "on the edge", and that Verstappen will "look at it and learn for future races."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/f1/story/_/id/17413337/christian-horner-says-max-verstappen-learn-belgium|title=Horner: Verstappen will learn from Belgium|publisher=ESPN|date=29 August 2016|access-date=4 November 2016|archive-date=7 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161107083945/http://www.espn.co.uk/f1/story/_/id/17413337/christian-horner-says-max-verstappen-learn-belgium|url-status=live}}</ref> In September, Formula One director [[Charlie Whiting]] called in Verstappen for a discussion, and later gave him a 'gentle warning' due to his aggressive driving.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/formula1/37258313|title=Italian GP: Max Verstappen given 'gentle warning' by FIA|publisher=BBC Sport|date=2 September 2016|access-date=4 November 2016|archive-date=6 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160906224118/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/formula1/37258313|url-status=live}}</ref> However, in October, drivers' concerns about Verstappen's defensive tactics led the FIA to disallow moving under braking.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/37741994|title=Formula 1 outlaws moving under braking after protests over Max Verstappen|publisher=BBC Sport|date=22 October 2016|access-date=12 February 2018|archive-date=2 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170902235036/http://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/37741994|url-status=live}}</ref>

At the [[2016 Brazilian Grand Prix]], Verstappen qualified fourth.<ref>{{cite web|title=Formula 1 Grande Premio do Brasil 2016 – Qualifying |url=http://www.formula1.com/en/results.html/2016/races/956/brazil/qualifying.html |publisher=Formula One |access-date=17 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161117112850/http://www.formula1.com/en/results.html/2016/races/956/brazil/qualifying.html |archive-date=17 November 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref> In a rain affected race, he almost hit the barrier after he slid on the main straight due to a loss of traction, causing [[oversteer]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Verstappen's Amazing Save in Brazil {{!}} F1 is...Heart-in-Mouth| date=14 March 2017 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wQCeQKQ7_vI|access-date=19 January 2022|archive-date=10 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220310040858/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wQCeQKQ7_vI|url-status=live}}</ref> After an additional tyre change from intermediates back to rain tyres, he ran in 16th place with just 15 laps remaining. Verstappen then made several overtakes in quick succession during the closing laps to eventually finish on the podium in third place.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Galloway |first1=James |title=Max Verstappen stole the show in Brazil GP, says Mercedes' Toto Wolff |url=http://www.skysports.com/f1/news/31381/10657138/max-verstappen-stole-the-show-in-brazil-gp-says-mercedes-toto-wolff |publisher=Sky Sports |access-date=17 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161117112959/http://www.skysports.com/f1/news/31381/10657138/max-verstappen-stole-the-show-in-brazil-gp-says-mercedes-toto-wolff |archive-date=17 November 2016 |date=14 November 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref> He received considerable praise for his performance: rival team Mercedes' team principal, [[Toto Wolff]], labelled it "The Verstappen Show", and described Verstappen's drive as "physics..being redefined".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gill |first1=Pete |last2=Esler |first2=William |title=Max Verstappen's Brazilian GP drive hailed as 'one of the best ever in F1' |url=http://www.skysports.com/f1/news/12040/10656712/max-verstappens-brazilian-gp-drive-hailed-as-one-of-the-best-ever-in-f1 |publisher=Sky Sports |access-date=17 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161117113003/http://www.skysports.com/f1/news/12040/10656712/max-verstappens-brazilian-gp-drive-hailed-as-one-of-the-best-ever-in-f1 |archive-date=17 November 2016 |date=14 November 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Max Verstappen's Masterclass {{!}} 2016 Brazilian Grand Prix| date=7 November 2017 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JO3q69x2sXA|access-date=22 January 2022|archive-date=22 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220122133251/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JO3q69x2sXA|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Verstappen's Brazil drive earns Senna/Schumacher comparisons|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/headlines/2016/11/f1-verstappen-brazil-gp-senna-schumacher-comparisons.html|access-date=22 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=22 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220122133250/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/headlines/2016/11/f1-verstappen-brazil-gp-senna-schumacher-comparisons.html|url-status=live}}</ref> However, Verstappen came under criticism from four-time world champion Sebastian Vettel, who stated that Verstappen had pushed him off the track at the Junção corner late in the race. The race stewards did not share Vettel's view and decided that no reprimand was warranted.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Edmondson |first1=Laurence |title=Vettel: Verstappen move was 'not correct' |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/f1/story/_/id/18041493/max-verstappen-move-was-not-correct |publisher=ESPN |access-date=17 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161117113518/http://www.espn.co.uk/f1/story/_/id/18041493/max-verstappen-move-was-not-correct |archive-date=17 November 2016 |date=14 November 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref>

====2017–2018: Reliability issues and rise to prominence====
[[File:2017 British Grand Prix (35127086003).jpg|thumb|right|Verstappen at the [[2017 British Grand Prix]]]]
During the first 14 races of the 2017 season, Verstappen suffered seven retirements, four due to mechanical issues,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/41068214|title=Max Verstappen: Red Bull's reliability unacceptable|publisher=BBC Sport|date=27 August 2017|access-date=12 February 2018|archive-date=30 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830010414/http://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/41068214|url-status=live}}</ref> and three due to first lap collisions in [[2017 Spanish Grand Prix|Spain]], [[2017 Austrian Grand Prix|Austria]] and [[2017 Singapore Grand Prix|Singapore]].<ref>[http://www.skysports.com/f1/news/12433/10877127/spanish-gp-valtteri-bottas-triggers-max-verstappen-kimi-raikkonen-crash Spanish GP: Valtteri Bottas triggers Max Verstappen-Kimi Raikkonen crash] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628083609/http://www.skysports.com/f1/news/12433/10877127/spanish-gp-valtteri-bottas-triggers-max-verstappen-kimi-raikkonen-crash |date=28 June 2017}} – James Galloway and Emily McNally, Sky Sports, 14 May 2017</ref> Of the races he finished, however, he claimed a third place in [[2017 Chinese Grand Prix|China]], and in another five races he finished fourth or fifth.<ref name="Standings"/>

From the [[2017 Malaysian Grand Prix|Malaysian Grand Prix]] onward, Verstappen enjoyed a surge of success. He won his second Formula One race at the 2017 Malaysian Grand Prix, a day after his 20th birthday, passing then three-time champion Lewis Hamilton for the lead in the early stages of the race.<ref>{{cite web|date=1 October 2017|title=Max Verstappen beats Lewis Hamilton to win F1's Malaysian Grand Prix|url=http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/oct/01/max-verstappen-lewis-hamilton-f1-malaysian-grand-prix-race-report-formula-one|access-date=19 January 2022|website=The Guardian|archive-date=15 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211215041014/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/oct/01/max-verstappen-lewis-hamilton-f1-malaysian-grand-prix-race-report-formula-one|url-status=live}}</ref> He finished second in the following [[2017 Japanese Grand Prix|race in Japan]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2017 Formula 1 Japanese Grand Prix – Race Result|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/results.html/2017/races/974/japan/race-result.html|publisher=Formula One|access-date=24 October 2017|archive-date=7 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007170355/https://www.formula1.com/en/results.html/2017/races/974/japan/race-result.html|url-status=live}}</ref> He then finished third at the [[2017 United States Grand Prix|United States]] Grand Prix, but was classified fourth after his final lap overtake on Kimi Räikkönen was deemed illegal.<ref>{{cite web|title=2017 Formula 1 United States Grand Prix – Race Result|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/results.html/2017/races/975/united-states.html|publisher=Formula One|access-date=24 October 2017|archive-date=22 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022215609/https://www.formula1.com/en/results.html/2017/races/975/united-states.html|url-status=live}}</ref> He won his third Formula One race at the [[2017 Mexican Grand Prix|Mexican Grand Prix]], after passing [[Sebastian Vettel]] on the opening lap.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/results.html/2017/races/976/mexico.html|title=Formula 1 Gran Premio de México 2017 – Race Result|publisher=Formula One|access-date=29 October 2017|archive-date=27 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027235005/https://www.formula1.com/en/results.html/2017/races/976/mexico.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[File:FIA F1 Austria 2018 Nr. 33 Verstappen.jpg|thumb|Verstappen at the [[2018 Austrian Grand Prix]]]]
In the first six races of the {{F1|2018}} season, Verstappen had been involved in at least one incident in each race. In [[2018 Australian Grand Prix|Australia]], he qualified fourth but fell behind [[Kevin Magnussen]] at the start.<ref>{{Cite web|title=F1 Results – 2018 Australian Grand Prix|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/2018/australian-grand-prix/results/qualifying|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=BBC Sport|archive-date=19 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220119232004/https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/2018/australian-grand-prix/results/qualifying|url-status=live}}</ref> In his attempts to retake the position he ran wide multiple times and damaged his car, with a spin causing him to fall further down the order. He recovered to eventually finish the race in sixth place.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/135028/early-damage-a-factor-in-verstappen-spin|title=Early damage a factor in Max Verstappen's Australian GP spin|last1=Mitchell|first1=Scott|date=25 March 2018|website=Autosport|publisher=[[Motorsport Network]]|last2=Cozens|first2=Jack|access-date=30 May 2018|archive-date=2 July 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200702202827/https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/135028/early-damage-a-factor-in-verstappen-spin|url-status=live}}</ref> At the next race in [[2018 Bahrain Grand Prix|Bahrain]], he crashed during qualifying and started in 15th place.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/red-bull-admits-foot-oscillation-caused-verstappen-bahrain-crash-5322006/5322006/|last1=Cooper|first1=Adam|title=Red Bull admits 'foot oscillation' caused Verstappen Bahrain crash|date=13 April 2018|website=Autosport|access-date=30 May 2018|archive-date=2 July 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200702202828/https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/red-bull-admits-foot-oscillation-caused-verstappen-bahrain-crash-5322006/5322006/|url-status=live}}</ref> He had a productive first lap after which he found himself in the points while challenging Lewis Hamilton. He attempted an overtake on the reigning World Champion at the start of lap two, but collided with the Mercedes driver and suffered a puncture that ultimately led to suspension damage, forcing him out of the race.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/f1/news/12514/11316602/bahrain-gp-sebastian-vettel-holds-off-valtteri-bottas-for-victory|title=Bahrain GP: Sebastian Vettel holds off Valtteri Bottas for victory|last=Gill|first=Pete|date=9 April 2018|publisher=[[Sky Sports F1]]|access-date=30 May 2018|archive-date=13 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613092534/http://www.skysports.com/f1/news/12514/11316602/bahrain-gp-sebastian-vettel-holds-off-valtteri-bottas-for-victory|url-status=live}}</ref>

At the next race in [[2018 Chinese Grand Prix|China]], Verstappen qualified fifth and had moved up to third at the end of the first lap.<ref>{{Citation|title=2018 Chinese Grand Prix: Race Highlights| date=15 April 2018 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uiub1DnUnkg|access-date=19 January 2022|archive-date=19 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220119232004/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uiub1DnUnkg|url-status=live}}</ref> Both Red Bull drivers pitted for fresh tyres during a safety car which left them with a tyre advantage over the front-runners ahead. In an overtake attempt on [[Sebastian Vettel]] for third place, Verstappen collided with the championship leader, causing him to fall to eighth and receive a 10-second penalty.<ref>{{Citation|title=Verstappen Runs into Vettel {{!}} 2018 Chinese Grand Prix| date=15 April 2018 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GR3Ls5tcp5A|access-date=19 January 2022|archive-date=13 October 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221013203419/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GR3Ls5tcp5A|url-status=live}}</ref> He recovered to fourth place, with his penalty causing him to be classified fifth. Teammate Ricciardo went on to win the race.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/135405/ricciardo-wins-vettel-and-verstappen-collide|title=Chinese Grand Prix: Ricciardo wins, Verstappen and Vettel collide|last=Mitchell|first=Scott|date=15 April 2018|website=Autosport|publisher=Motorsport Network|access-date=30 May 2018|archive-date=16 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416043910/https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/135405/ricciardo-wins-vettel-and-verstappen-collide|url-status=live}}</ref> In [[2018 Azerbaijan Grand Prix|Azerbaijan]], Verstappen was embroiled in a race-long battle with Ricciardo for fourth place. After numerous position changes between the two teammates during the race, Ricciardo ran into the back of Verstappen during an overtake attempt from which the Dutchman aggressively defended, causing the retirement of both cars.<ref>{{citation|title=All The Angles: Ricciardo and Verstappen Crash {{!}} 2018 Azerbaijan Grand Prix| date=29 April 2018 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=36YFQTFzZwU|access-date=19 January 2022|archive-date=13 October 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221013203426/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=36YFQTFzZwU|url-status=live}}</ref> Both drivers were blamed by the team and reprimanded by the stewards.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/f1/news/12433/11352821/max-verstappen-daniel-ricciardo-reprimanded-for-all-red-bull-azerbaijan-gp-crash|title=Max Verstappen, Daniel Ricciardo reprimanded for all-Red Bull Azerbaijan GP crash|last=Galloway|first=James|date=30 April 2018|publisher=Sky Sports F1|access-date=30 May 2018|archive-date=11 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180611131807/http://www.skysports.com/f1/news/12433/11352821/max-verstappen-daniel-ricciardo-reprimanded-for-all-red-bull-azerbaijan-gp-crash|url-status=live}}</ref> Verstappen bounced back in [[2018 Spanish Grand Prix|Spain]] with his first podium of the season by finishing third behind the Mercedes drivers, holding off [[Sebastian Vettel]]. However, the race was also not without incident as he had run into the back of [[Lance Stroll]] during the virtual safety car period, causing minor front wing damage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/features/2018/5/winners-and-losers--spanish-grand-prix-edition.html|title=Winners and Losers – Spanish Grand Prix edition|date=14 May 2018|publisher=Formula One|access-date=30 May 2018|archive-date=14 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180514153208/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/features/2018/5/winners-and-losers--spanish-grand-prix-edition.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

In [[2018 Monaco Grand Prix|Monaco]], Verstappen made another error and crashed near the end of the third free practice session in an incident which closely resembled a crash he had at the same spot [[2016 Monaco Grand Prix#Qualifying|two years earlier]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/136314/ricciardo-fastest-as-verstappen-crashes-in-fp3|title=Monaco GP F1 practice: Ricciardo fastest as Verstappen crashes in FP3|last=Mitchell|first=Scott|date=26 May 2018|website=Autosport|publisher=Motorsport Network|access-date=30 May 2018|archive-date=16 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016081329/https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/136314/ricciardo-fastest-as-verstappen-crashes-in-fp3|url-status=live}}</ref> His team could not repair his car in time for qualifying and Verstappen had to start the race from the back of the grid.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/44267114|title=Monaco Grand Prix: Max Verstappen crash 'unnecessary', says Red Bull's Helmut Marko|last=Benson|first=Andrew|date=26 May 2018|publisher=BBC Sport|access-date=30 May 2018|archive-date=14 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614165357/https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/44267114|url-status=live}}</ref> Verstappen did not compete and did not set a lap time in qualifying, therefore teammate Ricciardo pressed home Red Bull's advantage at the track by taking [[pole position]] and the race win. Verstappen managed to salvage two points by finishing ninth place, overtaking six cars on track.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/136339/ricciardo-wins-monaco-gp-despite-car-problem|title=Monaco Grand Prix: Daniel Ricciardo wins despite car problem|last=Mitchell|first=Scott|date=27 May 2018|website=Autosport|publisher=Motorsport Network|access-date=30 May 2018|archive-date=16 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016032724/https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/136339/ricciardo-wins-monaco-gp-despite-car-problem|url-status=live}}</ref> Team principal Christian Horner commented on Verstappen's start of the season, saying he "needed to stop making these mistakes" and that he could "learn from his teammate", while [[Helmut Marko]], head of driver development at Red Bull, said that Verstappen was "too impatient".<ref name=":1" /> Verstappen now lay in sixth place in the championship with 35 points, only three points ahead of [[Fernando Alonso]] in the McLaren, and 37 points behind his teammate in third, who had taken two wins in the first six races.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Woolcock|first=Adam|date=15 April 2018|title=F1 2018: Daniel Ricciardo wins Chinese Grand Prix – as it happened|work=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/live/2018/apr/15/formula-one-2018-chinese-grand-prix-live|access-date=19 January 2022|issn=0261-3077|archive-date=22 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180422223322/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/live/2018/apr/15/formula-one-2018-chinese-grand-prix-live|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=F1 REWIND: Watch Daniel Ricciardo's brilliant 2018 Monaco Grand Prix win|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.watch-live-join-our-stream-of-ricciardos-brilliant-2018-monaco-grand-prix.13UtM2BlgsaIn5QzBe6B4l.html|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=10 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220310074110/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.watch-live-join-our-stream-of-ricciardos-brilliant-2018-monaco-grand-prix.13UtM2BlgsaIn5QzBe6B4l.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

In [[2018 Canadian Grand Prix|Canada]], Verstappen topped all three practice sessions and qualified third, two-tenths off Sebastian Vettel in pole position.<ref>{{Cite web|title=F1 Results – 2018 Canadian Grand Prix|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/2018/canadian-grand-prix/results/qualifying|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=BBC Sport|archive-date=19 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220119232005/https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/2018/canadian-grand-prix/results/qualifying|url-status=live}}</ref> He eventually finished third and set the fastest lap of the race.<ref>{{Cite web|date=10 June 2018|title=Sebastian Vettel wins Canadian Grand Prix despite chequered flag mix-up|url=http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2018/jun/10/sebastian-vettel-wins-canadian-grand-prix-f1-championship-lewis-hamilton|access-date=19 January 2022|website=The Guardian|archive-date=16 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220116233202/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2018/jun/10/sebastian-vettel-wins-canadian-grand-prix-f1-championship-lewis-hamilton|url-status=live}}</ref> The following race in [[2018 French Grand Prix|France]] brought him second place.<ref>{{Cite web|title=F1 Results – 2018 French Grand Prix|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/2018/french-grand-prix/results|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=BBC Sport|archive-date=19 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220119232007/https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/2018/french-grand-prix/results|url-status=live}}</ref> In [[2018 Austrian Grand Prix|Austria]]—Red Bull's home track, he started fourth on the grid, passed Kimi Räikkönen before taking advantage of retirement from [[Valtteri Bottas]] and a botched pit-stop strategy by Lewis Hamilton, who later had to retire from fourth place, to claim the fourth race victory of his career.<ref>{{Citation|title=2018 Austrian Grand Prix: Race Highlights| date=July 2018 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JNmfS9PSeYg|access-date=19 January 2022|archive-date=19 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220119232005/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JNmfS9PSeYg|url-status=live}}</ref> In [[2018 British Grand Prix|Britain]], Verstappen was plagued by issues, finishing the first practice session early due to a gearbox problem and crashing in the second practice session before retiring from the race due to a brake problem.<ref>{{Cite web|date=8 July 2018|title=F1: The reason Max Verstappen spun then retired from the British GP|url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/motorsport/formula-one/f1-the-reason-max-verstappen-spun-then-retired-from-the-british-gp/news-story/bf90c9db2308a1b68936d240a7549c95|access-date=19 January 2022|work=Fox Sports|archive-date=19 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220119232005/https://www.foxsports.com.au/motorsport/formula-one/f1-the-reason-max-verstappen-spun-then-retired-from-the-british-gp/news-story/bf90c9db2308a1b68936d240a7549c95|url-status=live}}</ref> He would then finish fourth in [[2018 German Grand Prix|Germany]] after strategy errors let a recovering Hamilton get past him as he went on to win the race.<ref>{{Citation|title=2018 German Grand Prix: Race Highlights| date=22 July 2018 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gp-i8vtgzJE|access-date=19 January 2022|archive-date=13 October 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221013203408/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gp-i8vtgzJE|url-status=live}}</ref> Verstappen ended the first half of the season with a retirement in [[2018 Hungarian Grand Prix|Hungary]] and was narrowly behind his teammate in the championship due to his own recent resurgence and Ricciardo's unreliability.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Ricciardo: 'Weird' reliability inexplicable|url=https://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/ricciardo-weird-reliability-inexplicable/3202443/|access-date=19 January 2022|website=Motorsport.com|date=26 October 2018 |archive-date=24 April 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220424225311/https://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/ricciardo-weird-reliability-inexplicable/3202443/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=RACE: Verstappen retires early in Hungary|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/video.race-verstappen-retires-early-in-hungary.6060943592001.html|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=10 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220310022859/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/video.race-verstappen-retires-early-in-hungary.6060943592001.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

Verstappen enjoyed a very strong second half of the season, achieving podium finishes in [[2018 Belgian Grand Prix|Belgium]], [[2018 Singapore Grand Prix|Singapore]], [[2018 Japanese Grand Prix|Japan]] and the [[2018 United States Grand Prix|United States]], the latter of which he achieved second place having started from 18th on the grid due to a suspension failure in qualifying.<ref>{{Citation|title=2018 United States Grand Prix: Race Highlights| date=21 October 2018 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PNwPpqaLE60|access-date=19 January 2022|archive-date=19 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220119232524/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PNwPpqaLE60|url-status=live}}</ref> Following the qualifying session at the [[2018 Mexican Grand Prix|Mexican Grand Prix]], Verstappen revealed that a mechanical problem with his Red Bull under braking cost him any chance of becoming the youngest-ever Formula One pole-sitter. As a result, Ricciardo beat Verstappen to pole position by just 0.026 seconds.<ref>{{Citation|title=2018 Mexican Grand Prix: Qualifying Highlights| date=27 October 2018 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SVTDYyXP7E0|access-date=19 January 2022|archive-date=19 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220119233750/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SVTDYyXP7E0|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Max Verstappen unhappy after missing out on history-making pole position|url=https://www.skysports.com/f1/news/12433/11533294/max-verstappen-unhappy-after-missing-out-on-history-making-pole-position|access-date=12 February 2022|publisher=Sky Sports |archive-date=12 February 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220212120158/https://www.skysports.com/f1/news/12433/11533294/max-verstappen-unhappy-after-missing-out-on-history-making-pole-position|url-status=live}}</ref> Verstappen had a better start than Ricciardo and took the lead of the race into the first corner, overtaking the fast-starting Mercedes of Lewis Hamilton. Verstappen earned his fifth career win in Mexico.<ref>{{Citation|title=2018 Mexican Grand Prix: Race Highlights| date=28 October 2018 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d1-VK12FZhs|access-date=19 January 2022|archive-date=19 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220119233748/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d1-VK12FZhs|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Mexican Grand Prix 2018 report – Verstappen wins in Mexico as Hamilton takes fifth title|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.f1-2018-mexican-grand-prix-report.43bcuMZV3i8yk2a8kQw06w.html|access-date=17 February 2022|publisher=Formula One |archive-date=29 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181029014936/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.f1-2018-mexican-grand-prix-report.43bcuMZV3i8yk2a8kQw06w.html|url-status=live}}</ref> He was poised to win the [[2018 Brazilian Grand Prix]], having overtaken Räikkönen, Vettel, Bottas, and Hamilton. However, he collided with [[Force India]] driver [[Esteban Ocon]] who was trying to unlap himself on faster tyres.<ref>{{Citation|title=Verstappen And Ocon Collide {{!}} 2018 Brazilian Grand Prix| date=12 November 2018 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6LSAaVq4Dsw|access-date=19 January 2022|archive-date=19 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220119233744/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6LSAaVq4Dsw|url-status=live}}</ref> Ocon received a 10-second stop-and-go penalty for the incident. After the collision with Ocon, Verstappen finished in second place behind Hamilton. During an argument with Ocon after the race, Verstappen pushed the Force India driver, for which he was given two days of "public service" as a penalty by the FIA.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/139986/verstappen-given-public-service-for-ocon-shove|title=FIA gives Max Verstappen 'public service' for Esteban Ocon shove|last=Freeman|first=Glenn|website=Autosport|access-date=12 November 2018|archive-date=11 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181111214724/https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/139986/verstappen-given-public-service-for-ocon-shove|url-status=live}}</ref> He then finished his season with another podium as he finished third in Abu Dhabi.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/results.html/2018/races/999/abu-dhabi/race-result.html |title=Formula 1 2018 Etihad Airways Abu Dhabi Grand Prix – Race Result |publisher=Formula One |date=25 November 2018 |access-date=25 November 2018 |archive-date=13 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210113155249/https://www.formula1.com/en/results.html/2018/races/999/abu-dhabi/race-result.html |url-status=live}}</ref>

Verstappen ended the season in fourth place in the championship with 249 points, claiming two wins, eleven podium finishes, and two fastest laps.<ref>{{cite web|title=Max Verstappen in 2018|url=https://www.racing-statistics.com/en/drivers/compare/max-verstappen/seasons/2018|access-date=19 December 2021|website=Formula 1 Statistics|archive-date=19 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211219093227/https://www.racing-statistics.com/en/drivers/compare/max-verstappen/seasons/2018|url-status=live}}</ref>

====2019–2020: Dominance over teammates====
[[File:Max Verstappen during Hungarian Formula 1 GP.jpg|thumb|Verstappen at the [[2019 Hungarian Grand Prix]], where he started on pole position for the first time in his career]]
In [[2019 Formula One World Championship|2019]] Red Bull switched from Renault to [[Honda in Formula One|Honda]] power units.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Red Bull agree deal to run Honda engine technology until 2025|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.breaking-red-bull-agree-deal-to-run-honda-engine-technology-until-2025.3wmTSMrtsv6miuwqApz8IT.html|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=15 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210215215037/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.breaking-red-bull-agree-deal-to-run-honda-engine-technology-until-2025.3wmTSMrtsv6miuwqApz8IT.html|url-status=live}}</ref> After Ricciardo moved to the [[Renault in Formula One|Renault]] team for 2019, Verstappen was joined at Red Bull by [[Pierre Gasly]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Pierre Gasly joins Red Bull for 2019|url=https://www.skysports.com/f1/news/12433/11477951/pierre-gasly-joins-red-bull-for-f1-2019|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Sky Sports|archive-date=5 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220305224221/https://www.skysports.com/f1/news/12433/11477951/pierre-gasly-joins-red-bull-for-f1-2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Verstappen qualified in fourth and finished third in [[2019 Australian Grand Prix|Australia]], the first podium finish for a [[Honda in Formula One|Honda]]-powered driver since the [[2008 British Grand Prix]].<ref>{{Cite web|date=17 March 2019|title=F1 Australian Grand Prix 2019: Max Verstappen sends ominous Red Bull message after Honda milestone|url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/motorsport/formula-one/f1-australian-grand-prix-2019-max-verstappen-race-results-red-bull-honda-renault-video-latest-news/news-story/9d6d29140487e11eacfa8296e1f95f22|access-date=11 October 2021|work=Fox Sports|archive-date=28 October 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211028172923/https://www.foxsports.com.au/motorsport/formula-one/f1-australian-grand-prix-2019-max-verstappen-race-results-red-bull-honda-renault-video-latest-news/news-story/9d6d29140487e11eacfa8296e1f95f22|url-status=live}}</ref> Verstappen was on course for a second third-place finish in [[2019 Bahrain Grand Prix|Bahrain]] before a late safety car prevented him from overtaking Charles Leclerc's ailing Ferrari, keeping him in fourth place.<ref>{{Citation|title=2019 Bahrain Grand Prix: Race Highlights| date=31 March 2019 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0VjWY--QdMA|access-date=19 January 2022|archive-date=24 April 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220424225323/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0VjWY--QdMA|url-status=live}}</ref> Two more fourth-place finishes followed in [[2019 Chinese Grand Prix|China]] and [[2019 Azerbaijan Grand Prix|Azerbaijan]], and a podium in [[2019 Spanish Grand Prix|Spain]] in third place.<ref>{{Cite web|title=F1 Results – 2019 Spanish Grand Prix|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/2019/spanish-grand-prix/results|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=BBC Sport|archive-date=24 April 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220424225314/https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/2019/spanish-grand-prix/results|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=F1 Results – 2019 Azerbaijan Grand Prix|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/2019/azerbaijan-grand-prix/results/race|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=BBC Sport|archive-date=24 April 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220424225311/https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/2019/azerbaijan-grand-prix/results/race|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=F1 Results – 2019 Chinese Grand Prix|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/2019/chinese-grand-prix/results|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=BBC Sport|archive-date=13 October 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221013203417/https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/2019/chinese-grand-prix/results|url-status=live}}</ref> In [[2019 Monaco Grand Prix|Monaco]], Verstappen qualified in third place. He was released into the path of Valtteri Bottas during the drivers' pit stops, gaining second place but receiving a 5-second penalty as a result. Verstappen crossed the line in second place but was demoted to fourth by the penalty.<ref>{{Cite web|date=26 May 2019|title=Verstappen given penalty points for failing to avoid contact · RaceFans|url=https://www.racefans.net/2019/05/26/verstappen-given-penalty-points-for-failing-to-avoid-contact/|access-date=11 October 2021|website=RaceFans|archive-date=23 October 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211023170821/https://www.racefans.net/2019/05/26/verstappen-given-penalty-points-for-failing-to-avoid-contact/|url-status=live}}</ref>

In [[2019 Canadian Grand Prix|Canada]], Verstappen's final lap in the second qualifying session was hampered by a red flag brought out by [[Kevin Magnussen]]'s crash. This caused Verstappen to qualify 11th and start the race in ninth place.<ref>{{Cite web|date=8 June 2019|title=F1 Canadian Grand Prix 2019 qualifying results: Daniel Ricciardo stuns with best result since October as Sebastian Vettel snatches pole|url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/motorsport/formula-one/f1-canadian-grand-prix-2019-live-qualifying-results-timings-daniel-ricciardo-renault-lewis-hamilton-timesheets-updates-blog/news-story/95ac6b8933fff5af9a310a512de60366|url-status=live|access-date=11 January 2022|work=Fox Sports|archive-date=11 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220111041408/https://www.foxsports.com.au/motorsport/formula-one/f1-canadian-grand-prix-2019-live-qualifying-results-timings-daniel-ricciardo-renault-lewis-hamilton-timesheets-updates-blog/news-story/95ac6b8933fff5af9a310a512de60366}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Fair|first=Asher|date=9 June 2019|title=Formula 1: Provisional starting grid for 2019 Canadian Grand Prix|url=https://beyondtheflag.com/2019/06/09/formula-1-provisional-starting-grid-2019-canadian-grand-prix/|url-status=live|access-date=11 January 2022|website=Beyond the Flag|archive-date=11 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220111041417/https://beyondtheflag.com/2019/06/09/formula-1-provisional-starting-grid-2019-canadian-grand-prix/}}</ref> He later recovered to finish fifth.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Richards|first=Giles|date=9 June 2019|title=Lewis Hamilton handed Canadian Grand Prix win after Vettel's penalty pain|url=http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/jun/09/lewis-hamilton-canadian-grand-prix-vettel-penalty|url-status=live|access-date=11 January 2022|website=The Guardian|archive-date=5 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220105160525/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/jun/09/lewis-hamilton-canadian-grand-prix-vettel-penalty}}</ref> In [[2019 French Grand Prix|France]] he started and finished in fourth place.<ref>{{Cite web|title=French Grand Prix 2019 – F1 Race|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/racing/2019/France.html|url-status=live|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=28 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141028202800/https://www.formula1.com/en/racing/2019/France.html}}</ref> In [[2019 Austrian Grand Prix|Austria]], Verstappen started third but suffered a poor start, dropping down to eighth. After a charge towards the front, he made his way up to second before controversially passing Leclerc for the lead of the race with three laps to go.<ref>{{Citation|title=Verstappen's Stunning Fightback {{!}} 2019 Austrian Grand Prix| date=30 June 2019 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cV0G1zN8kJU|access-date=19 January 2022|archive-date=13 October 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221013203250/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cV0G1zN8kJU|url-status=live}}</ref> This marked the first Honda-powered race victory since the [[2006 Hungarian Grand Prix]].<ref>{{Cite news|last1=McVeigh (earlier)|first1=Niall|last2=Unwin (now)|first2=Will|date=30 June 2019|title=F1: Verstappen's win stands after Austrian Grand Prix stewards inquiry – as it happened|work=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/live/2019/jun/30/f1-formula-one-austrian-grand-prix-live|access-date=11 January 2022|issn=0261-3077|archive-date=11 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220111041738/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/live/2019/jun/30/f1-formula-one-austrian-grand-prix-live|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=1 July 2019|title=Honda hails new beginning after first F1 win since 2006|url=https://www.autoblog.com/2019/07/01/honda-hail-new-beginning-after-first-f1-win-since-2006/|url-status=live|access-date=11 January 2022|website=Autoblog|archive-date=13 October 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221013203242/https://www.autoblog.com/2019/07/01/honda-hail-new-beginning-after-first-f1-win-since-2006/}}</ref> In [[2019 British Grand Prix|Britain]], Verstappen, running in third place,<ref>{{Cite web|last=Simpson|first=Christopher|date=12 July 2019|title=F1 British Grand Prix 2019 Qualifying: Results, Times from Friday's Practice|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2845285-british-f1-grand-prix-2019-qualifying-results-times-from-fridays-practice|url-status=live|access-date=11 January 2022|website=Bleacher Report|archive-date=13 October 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221013203242/https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2845285-british-f1-grand-prix-2019-qualifying-results-times-from-fridays-practice}}</ref> was hit from behind during an overtake attempt by Sebastian Vettel and spun into the gravel. Verstappen was able to continue and crossed the line in fifth place.<ref>{{Cite web|date=14 July 2019|title=British Grand Prix 2019 race report: Hamilton victorious as Verstappen and Vettel collide in Silverstone thriller|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.hamilton-victorious-as-verstappen-and-vettel-collide-in-silverstone.3yHjP4nXKPkt4HYJQ7Bagt.html|url-status=live|access-date=11 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=14 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190714153942/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.hamilton-victorious-as-verstappen-and-vettel-collide-in-silverstone.3yHjP4nXKPkt4HYJQ7Bagt.html}}</ref>

The wet and chaotic [[2019 German Grand Prix|German Grand Prix]] began similarly to the race in Austria for Verstappen, as a poor start caused him to fall behind. However, he would inherit the lead midway through the race after a crash by race leader Hamilton.<ref>{{Citation|title=2019 German Grand Prix: Race Highlights| date=28 July 2019 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RYHQmBULhLc|access-date=19 January 2022|archive-date=19 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220119235641/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RYHQmBULhLc|url-status=live}}</ref> Verstappen would go on to extend his lead after the track began to dry, claiming his second victory of the season.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Richards|first=Giles|date=28 July 2019|title=Max Verstappen wins thrilling German GP after Lewis Hamilton error|url=http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/jul/28/max-verstappen-wins-german-grand-prix-hamilton-error|url-status=live|access-date=29 December 2021|website=The Guardian|archive-date=15 November 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211115040807/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/jul/28/max-verstappen-wins-german-grand-prix-hamilton-error}}</ref> In [[2019 Hungarian Grand Prix|Hungary]], he claimed the first pole position of his career and led most of the race before being passed in the closing laps by Hamilton, who had made another stop for fresh tyres in a gamble to catch the leader.<ref>{{Cite web|date=4 August 2019|title=Hungarian Grand Prix 2019 F1 race report: Hamilton brilliantly hunts down Verstappen to snatch Hungary victory|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.hamilton-brilliantly-hunts-down-verstappen-to-snatch-hungary-victory.4QPgPYGdCXqeEirMjUEhZU.html|url-status=live|access-date=29 December 2021|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=29 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211229031344/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.hamilton-brilliantly-hunts-down-verstappen-to-snatch-hungary-victory.4QPgPYGdCXqeEirMjUEhZU.html}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Verstappen takes maiden career pole in thrilling Hungary qualifying|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-takes-maiden-career-pole-in-thrilling-hungary-qualifying.5AABsomaDmZaBusQxjCZuP.html|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=18 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220118131304/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-takes-maiden-career-pole-in-thrilling-hungary-qualifying.5AABsomaDmZaBusQxjCZuP.html|url-status=live}}</ref>
[[File:Fórmula 1 – Grande Prêmio do Brasil de F1 2019 (49080565726).jpg|thumb|right|Verstappen on the podium after winning the [[2019 Brazilian Grand Prix]]]]
Before the [[2019 Belgian Grand Prix|Belgian Grand Prix]], Verstappen received a new teammate in Alexander Albon after Pierre Gasly was demoted back to Toro Rosso.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Albon to replace Gasly at Red Bull from Belgium|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.albon-to-replace-gasly-at-red-bull-from-belgium.5f9BkwxuJ5TF86EPKqqwJa.html|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=24 December 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201224174052/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.albon-to-replace-gasly-at-red-bull-from-belgium.5f9BkwxuJ5TF86EPKqqwJa.html|url-status=live}}</ref> In the race, Verstappen had a poor start and collided with Kimi Räikkönen at the first corner, resulting in suspension damage and causing Verstappen's first retirement of the season.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Verstappen and Raikkonen bemoan first-lap clash|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-and-raikkonen-bemoan-first-lap-clash.4LEpXoR5Ha6QXl9xd2Ovty.html|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=3 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190903173008/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-and-raikkonen-bemoan-first-lap-clash.4LEpXoR5Ha6QXl9xd2Ovty.html|url-status=live}}</ref> In [[2019 Italian Grand Prix|Italy]], he did not set a time during qualifying after his car lost power in Q1, but he was already required to start from the back of the grid due to an engine component penalty.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Media|first=P. A.|date=4 September 2019|title=Penalty shunts Max Verstappen to back of F1 grid for Italian Grand Prix|url=http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/sep/04/max-verstappen-engine-penalty-monza-italian-grand-prix-back-grid|access-date=19 January 2022|website=The Guardian|archive-date=24 April 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220424225312/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/sep/04/max-verstappen-engine-penalty-monza-italian-grand-prix-back-grid|url-status=live}}</ref> After damaging his front wing on the first lap, he recovered to finish the race in eighth place.<ref>{{Citation|title=2019 Italian Grand Prix: Race Highlights| date=8 September 2019 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=h-ce3gPMsGc|access-date=19 January 2022|archive-date=3 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303104046/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=h-ce3gPMsGc&app=desktop|url-status=live}}</ref> Third and fourth-place finishes followed in [[2019 Singapore Grand Prix|Singapore]] and [[2019 Russian Grand Prix|Russia]] respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Singapore Grand Prix 2019 – F1 Race|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/racing/2019/Singapore.html|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=11 November 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201111192803/https://www.formula1.com/en/racing/2019/Singapore.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=F1 Results – 2019 Russian Grand Prix|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/2019/russian-grand-prix/results|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=BBC Sport|archive-date=24 April 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220424225311/https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/2019/russian-grand-prix/results|url-status=live}}</ref> After suffering damage in a first-lap collision with Charles Leclerc in [[2019 Japanese Grand Prix|Japan]], Verstappen suffered his second retirement of the season.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Japanese Grand Prix 2019: Verstappen blasts 'irresponsible' Leclerc after Lap 1 contact|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-blasts-irresponsible-leclerc-after-lap-1-contact.4yO6ylOGvL0uzhJZ98myCz.html|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=24 April 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220424225325/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-blasts-irresponsible-leclerc-after-lap-1-contact.4yO6ylOGvL0uzhJZ98myCz.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

In [[2019 Mexican Grand Prix|Mexico]], he qualified in first place after setting the fastest lap-time of the session, before being handed a grid penalty for ignoring [[Racing flags#Yellow flag|yellow flags]] after a crash by Valtteri Bottas.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Mexican Grand Prix 2019 qualifying report: Verstappen takes sensational Mexican pole as Bottas crashes|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-takes-sensational-mexican-pole-as-bottas-suffers-big-crash.2iQWb1vLhcfSRBothUZyzd.html|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=28 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191028220105/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-takes-sensational-mexican-pole-as-bottas-suffers-big-crash.2iQWb1vLhcfSRBothUZyzd.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Verstappen suffered a puncture early in the race after making contact with Bottas, falling to the back of the field before eventually recovering to sixth place.<ref>{{Cite web|date=27 October 2019|title=Mexican Grand Prix 2019 report & highlights: Hamilton closes in on title with supreme Mexico victory|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.mexican-grand-prix-2019-report-and-highlights.2GCUEuCYRquG0pcZeGZuYz.html|url-status=live|access-date=29 December 2021|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=28 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191028191133/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.mexican-grand-prix-2019-report-and-highlights.2GCUEuCYRquG0pcZeGZuYz.html}}</ref> A third-place finish in the [[2019 United States Grand Prix|United States]] followed, before Verstappen took the second pole position of his career with a 1:07.508 pole lap time in [[2019 Brazilian Grand Prix|Brazil]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=United States Grand Prix 2019 – F1 Race|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/racing/2019/United_States.html|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=13 September 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200913021847/https://www.formula1.com/en/racing/2019/United_States.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Brazilian Grand Prix 2019 qualifying report: Brazilian Grand Prix report: Verstappen snatches sensational Interlagos pole|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-snatches-sensational-interlagos-pole.6QOPSwc0ZAKtVuAsXoaoDI.html|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=12 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220112034257/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-snatches-sensational-interlagos-pole.6QOPSwc0ZAKtVuAsXoaoDI.html|url-status=live}}</ref> In a chaotic race, he passed Lewis Hamilton for the lead on two occasions before going on to claim his third victory of the season.<ref>{{Citation|title=2019 Brazilian Grand Prix: Race Highlights| date=17 November 2019 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3WZeoOkMf0Y|access-date=19 January 2022|archive-date=24 April 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220424225323/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3WZeoOkMf0Y|url-status=live}}</ref> Verstappen ended the season with a second-place finish in [[2019 Abu Dhabi Grand Prix|Abu Dhabi]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Abu Dhabi Grand Prix 2019 race report and highlights: Hamilton rounds off title-winning season with dominant Abu Dhabi win|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.abu-dhabi-grand-prix-2019-race-report-highlights.3W60C6jaqAMKYqcblkhGqg.html|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=2 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191202061826/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.abu-dhabi-grand-prix-2019-race-report-highlights.3W60C6jaqAMKYqcblkhGqg.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

Verstappen finished the 2019 season in third place in the championship with 278 points. He claimed three race victories, nine podium finishes, two pole positions, and three fastest laps.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Max Verstappen in 2019|url=https://www.racing-statistics.com/en/drivers/compare/max-verstappen/seasons/2019|access-date=19 December 2021|website=Formula 1 Statistics|archive-date=19 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211219094726/https://www.racing-statistics.com/en/drivers/compare/max-verstappen/seasons/2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[File:Max Verstappen, 2020 pre-season testing.jpg|thumb|Verstappen at [[2020 Formula One pre-season testing|pre-season testing in 2020]]]]
Verstappen continued to race for Red Bull in {{F1|2020}}, alongside Albon. At the [[2020 Austrian Grand Prix]], he started second, but retired early in the race after a flywheel-related problem caused an electronic issue within the power unit.<ref>{{Cite web|date=10 July 2020|title=Albon's DNF likely caused by Hamilton clash, not Honda fault|url=https://the-race.com/formula-1/albons-dnf-likely-caused-by-hamilton-clash-not-honda-fault/|access-date=21 July 2020|website=The Race|archive-date=21 July 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200721123813/https://the-race.com/formula-1/albons-dnf-likely-caused-by-hamilton-clash-not-honda-fault/|url-status=live}}</ref> Honda introduced countermeasures in response to the retirement.<ref>{{Cite web|date=9 July 2020|title=Red Bull, Honda have countermeasures for engine issues|url=https://the-race.com/formula-1/honda-has-countermeasures-for-red-bulls-engine-issues/|access-date=21 July 2020|website=The Race|archive-date=21 July 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200721123808/https://the-race.com/formula-1/honda-has-countermeasures-for-red-bulls-engine-issues/|url-status=live}}</ref>

At the [[2020 Hungarian Grand Prix]], he crashed in wet conditions during the [[formation lap]] while he was on his way to the starting grid,<ref>{{Citation|title=Max Verstappen Crashes On Way To Grid {{!}} 2020 Hungarian Grand Prix| date=19 July 2020 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k-HpHDpeF8E|access-date=20 January 2022|archive-date=20 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220120003458/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k-HpHDpeF8E|url-status=live}}</ref> but he was able to drive the car back to the grid where his mechanics fixed the suspension of the car in the short time that was left before the start of the race.<ref>{{Citation|title=INSIDE STORY: How Red Bull Performed a Mechanical Miracle in Hungary| date=15 January 2021 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IGwm1QmwN9s|access-date=20 January 2022|archive-date=20 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220120003454/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IGwm1QmwN9s|url-status=live}}</ref> After the repairs, Verstappen progressed from seventh place on the grid to second place by the end of the race.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.second-feels-like-a-win-says-verstappen-as-he-recovers-from-pre-race-crash.5rbSAYCw1F215d1dlFvW8A.html|title='Second feels like a win' says Verstappen as he recovers from pre-race crash to podium|publisher=Formula One|access-date=21 July 2020|archive-date=20 July 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200720204302/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.second-feels-like-a-win-says-verstappen-as-he-recovers-from-pre-race-crash.5rbSAYCw1F215d1dlFvW8A.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Verstappen won the [[70th Anniversary Grand Prix]] at [[Silverstone Circuit|Silverstone]], having started from fourth.<ref name="MVvolgensGR">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2020/aug/09/f1-max-verstappen-70th-anniversary-grand-prix-lewis-hamilton|title=Max Verstappen roars to spectacular victory in 70th Anniversary Grand Prix|author=Giles Richards|date=9 August 2020|publisher=[[The Guardian]], London|access-date=9 August 2020|archive-date=9 August 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200809153202/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2020/aug/09/f1-max-verstappen-70th-anniversary-grand-prix-lewis-hamilton|url-status=live}}</ref>

Verstappen clinched second place at the [[2020 Spanish Grand Prix|Spanish Grand Prix]], after qualifying in third.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Spanish Grand Prix 2020 – F1 Race|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/racing/2020/Spain.html|url-status=live|access-date=20 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=11 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210111012227/https://www.formula1.com/en/racing/2020/Spain.html}}</ref> At the [[2020 Belgian Grand Prix]], he scored a podium in third place, following his third place on the starting grid.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Belgian Grand Prix 2020 – F1 Race|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/racing/2020/Belgium.html|url-status=live|access-date=20 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=19 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210119083704/https://www.formula1.com/en/racing/2020/Belgium.html}}</ref> He suffered from two consecutive DNFs at the [[2020 Italian Grand Prix|Italian]] and [[2020 Tuscan Grand Prix|Tuscan]] Grands Prix after which he lost second place in the Championship.<ref>{{Citation|title=2020 Italian Grand Prix: Race Highlights| date=6 September 2020 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TB5yhZdF8SI|access-date=20 January 2022|archive-date=20 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220120003452/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TB5yhZdF8SI|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=2020 Tuscan Grand Prix: Race Highlights| date=13 September 2020 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R-Yq1AlIwsc|access-date=20 January 2022|archive-date=20 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220120003456/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R-Yq1AlIwsc|url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[2020 Russian Grand Prix|Russian Grand Prix]], Verstappen finished the race in second, his seventh podium finish of 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Russian Grand Prix 2020 – F1 Race|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/racing/2020/Russia.html|url-status=live|access-date=20 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=19 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210119083834/https://www.formula1.com/en/racing/2020/Russia.html}}</ref> At the [[2020 Eifel Grand Prix|Eifel Grand Prix]], Verstappen finished in second after qualifying in third.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Eifel Grand Prix 2020 – German F1 Race|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/racing/2020/Germany.html|access-date=20 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=19 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210119083909/https://www.formula1.com/en/racing/2020/Germany.html|url-status=live}}</ref> He also managed to get the fastest lap of the race.<ref>{{Citation|title=Verstappen's Nurburgring Lap Record: Fastest Lap {{!}} 2020 Eifel Grand Prix {{!}} DHL| date=12 October 2020 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1TRkAjsB7MA|access-date=20 January 2022|archive-date=20 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220120003500/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1TRkAjsB7MA|url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[2020 Portuguese Grand Prix|Portuguese Grand Prix]], Verstappen qualified third, however a poor first lap meant that he dropped back down the order to fifth place. He recovered to third and took his 40th podium in Formula 1.<ref>{{Citation|title=2020 Portuguese Grand Prix: Race Highlights| date=25 October 2020 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nQ8du5ysxTI|access-date=20 January 2022|archive-date=25 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211225143139/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nQ8du5ysxTI|url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[2020 Emilia Romagna Grand Prix|Emilia Romagna Grand Prix]], Verstappen looked set to claim second due to [[Valtteri Bottas]]' ailing Mercedes slowing down, but a sudden puncture denied him any chance of a podium finish; Verstappen spun, resulting in his fourth retirement of the 2020 season.<ref>{{Citation|title=Verstappen Crashes Out of Podium Position After Right Rear Failure| date=November 2020 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gYcA_ivpSxE|access-date=19 January 2022|archive-date=13 October 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221013203414/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gYcA_ivpSxE|url-status=live}}</ref>

During Free Practice for the Portuguese Grand Prix, Verstappen was criticised for comments he made on the team radio after a collision with [[Lance Stroll]], where he used the words "retard" and "mongol" in response to the clash. Verstappen admitted following the session that the word choices he used were "not correct". The Mongolian government and the Mongol identity asked Verstappen to apologise for the comments; the Mongolian government also urged the [[Fédération Internationale de l'Automobile|FIA]] to take action on the comments he made.<ref>{{cite web |last=Cooper |first=Adam |title=Portimao radio comments 'not correct', says Verstappen |website=Motorsport.com |url=https://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/verstappen-radio-outburst-portugal-stroll/4901418/ |date=30 October 2020 |access-date=12 November 2020 |archive-date=1 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201101033201/https://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/verstappen-radio-outburst-portugal-stroll/4901418/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Boxall-Legge |first=Jake |title=Mongolian government wants FIA to act on Verstappen comments |website=Motorsport.com |url=https://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/mongolia-foreign-minister-letter-verstappen-comments/4901947/ |date=31 October 2020 |access-date=12 November 2020 |archive-date=10 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201110110951/https://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/mongolia-foreign-minister-letter-verstappen-comments/4901947/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

Verstappen finished the 2020 season in third place in the championship with 214 points. He claimed two race victories, eleven podium finishes, one pole position, and three fastest laps.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Max Verstappen in 2020|url=https://www.racing-statistics.com/en/drivers/compare/max-verstappen/seasons/2020|access-date=19 December 2021|website=Formula 1 Statistics|archive-date=19 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211219094724/https://www.racing-statistics.com/en/drivers/compare/max-verstappen/seasons/2020|url-status=live}}</ref>

====2021: World Champion amid title battle vs. Hamilton====
[[File:FIA F1 Austria 2021 Nr. 33 Verstappen.jpg|thumb|Verstappen at the 2021 Austrian Grand Prix]]
At the [[2021 Bahrain Grand Prix|Bahrain Grand Prix]], Verstappen topped all the practice sessions and subsequently took a career fourth pole position. This was the first time he achieved back-to-back pole positions.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Max Verstappen takes pole position in F1 Bahrain Grand Prix, Daniel Ricciardo sixth|date=27 March 2021|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2021-03-28/max-verstappen-takes-pole-position-in-f1-bahrain-grand-prix/100033884|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=30 March 2021|archive-date=30 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210330114816/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2021-03-28/max-verstappen-takes-pole-position-in-f1-bahrain-grand-prix/100033884|url-status=live}}</ref> He fought Lewis Hamilton for the race victory, and on lap 53 Verstappen overtook Hamilton, but went off track whilst doing so, resulting in him being instructed by race control to let Hamilton back into the lead and ultimately finishing second behind Hamilton.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.it-is-what-it-is-verstappen-philosophical-about-surrendering-lead-to.1etBIWyqgV0mdhLUCGjqyJ.html|title='It is what it is' – Verstappen philosophical about surrendering lead to Hamilton following off-track pass|publisher=Formula One|access-date=30 March 2021|archive-date=30 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210330120727/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.it-is-what-it-is-verstappen-philosophical-about-surrendering-lead-to.1etBIWyqgV0mdhLUCGjqyJ.html|url-status=live}}</ref> At the next race, the [[2021 Emilia Romagna Grand Prix|Emilia Romagna Grand Prix]], Verstappen qualified third with teammate [[Sergio Pérez]] second, marking the first time he was out-qualified by a teammate since the [[2019 Italian Grand Prix]].<ref>{{Cite web|title='We're not robots' – Verstappen on 'messy' Q3 that led to being out-qualified by a team mate for first time since 2018|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.were-not-robots-verstappen-on-messy-q3-that-led-to-being-out-qualified-by-a.a7GbWPG2MnJEtyXOmP1x6.html|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=20 October 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211020100943/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.were-not-robots-verstappen-on-messy-q3-that-led-to-being-out-qualified-by-a.a7GbWPG2MnJEtyXOmP1x6.html|url-status=live}}</ref> At the race start, Verstappen was able to pass both Pérez and pole-sitter Lewis Hamilton to take the lead. He remained in the lead after the first round of pit stops as well as the restart, following the race being suspended on lap 33. Rival Hamilton finished second, reducing his championship lead over Verstappen to one point.<ref>{{Citation|title=Race Highlights {{!}} 2021 Emilia Romagna Grand Prix| date=18 April 2021 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ds0BC8RDJ5o|access-date=19 January 2022|archive-date=13 October 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221013203252/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ds0BC8RDJ5o|url-status=live}}</ref> In the following [[2021 Portuguese Grand Prix|Portuguese Grand Prix]], Verstappen finished second after a long battle with Lewis Hamilton.<ref>{{Citation|title=Race Highlights {{!}} 2021 Portuguese Grand Prix| date=2 May 2021 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-9-8gvYantk|access-date=19 January 2022|archive-date=24 April 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220424225321/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-9-8gvYantk|url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[2021 Spanish Grand Prix|Spanish Grand Prix]], the battle between Verstappen and Hamilton continued, with Hamilton employing a faster two-stop strategy versus Verstappen's one-stop race. This provided Hamilton the advantage of faster tyres, allowing him to overtake Verstappen with several laps remaining in the race. Hamilton took the victory, with Verstappen taking second and the fastest lap, increasing Hamilton's championship lead to 14 points.<ref>{{Cite web|title=2021 Spanish Grand Prix race report and highlights: Late pass secures Hamilton victory in Spain after race-long battle with Verstappen|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.late-pass-secures-hamilton-victory-in-spain-after-race-long-battle-with.5xOxaR8dsRf8zn11GGd8dN.html|access-date=18 May 2021|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=9 May 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210509175353/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.late-pass-secures-hamilton-victory-in-spain-after-race-long-battle-with.5xOxaR8dsRf8zn11GGd8dN.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

At the next race in [[2021 Monaco Grand Prix|Monaco]], Verstappen qualified second behind [[Charles Leclerc]],<ref>{{Cite web|title=2021 Monaco GP Qualifying: Verstappen rages at Leclerc crash red flags|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/video.2021-monaco-gp-qualifying-verstappen-rages-at-leclerc-crash-red-flags.1700470908172196475.html|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=10 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220310032538/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/video.2021-monaco-gp-qualifying-verstappen-rages-at-leclerc-crash-red-flags.1700470908172196475.html|url-status=live}}</ref> but Leclerc suffered a driveshaft failure on the way to the grid and was unable to start the race. Verstappen controlled the race from the front on the way to victory. Hamilton (who qualified seventh) finished seventh, though claiming an extra championship point by setting the fastest race lap. The result enabled Verstappen to take the lead in the Drivers' Championship for the first time in his career, by a margin of four points over Hamilton.<ref>{{cite web |last=Benson |first=Andrew |title=Monaco Grand Prix: Max Verstappen takes title lead from Lewis Hamilton with win |publisher=BBC Sport |date=23 May 2021 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/formula1/57220586 |access-date=23 May 2021 |archive-date=23 May 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210523152235/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/formula1/57220586 |url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[2021 Azerbaijan Grand Prix|Azerbaijan Grand Prix]], Verstappen qualified third behind Leclerc and Hamilton.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Verstappen curses 'stupid' qualifying session in Baku as he loses another chance of pole to red flag|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-curses-stupid-qualifying-in-baku-as-he-loses-another-chance-of.71o8PO388LO4nTLXqmE0SC.html|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=25 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220125074130/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-curses-stupid-qualifying-in-baku-as-he-loses-another-chance-of.71o8PO388LO4nTLXqmE0SC.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Verstappen and Hamilton passed Leclerc in the opening laps before Verstappen took the lead by way of a faster pitstop. Verstappen would comfortably hold the lead until lap 46 when he suffered a tyre failure causing him to crash at high speed and retire.<ref>{{Citation|title=Verstappen Crashes Out of Lead After Left Rear Failure {{!}} 2021 Azerbaijan Grand Prix| date=6 June 2021 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mgAinVHFwls|access-date=19 January 2022|archive-date=28 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220128103451/https://www.youtube.com/watch?t=32&v=mgAinVHFwls&feature=youtu.be|url-status=live}}</ref> A mistake by Hamilton on the restart dropped him to last place, meaning Verstappen maintained his championship lead.<ref>{{Cite web|title=2021 Azerbaijan Grand Prix race report and highlights: Perez beats Vettel to Baku victory after Verstappen crashes out from lead late on|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.perez-beats-vettel-to-baku-victory-after-verstappen-crashes-out-from-lead.aLIxuNGxwBFgZ4Z8OhuRw.html|access-date=29 June 2021|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=10 June 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210610172247/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.perez-beats-vettel-to-baku-victory-after-verstappen-crashes-out-from-lead.aLIxuNGxwBFgZ4Z8OhuRw.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Verstappen took pole for the [[2021 French Grand Prix|French Grand Prix]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Max Verstappen's Onboard Pole Lap {{!}} 2021 French Grand Prix| date=19 June 2021 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gq5-tSxKIcE|access-date=19 January 2022|archive-date=10 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220310191135/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gq5-tSxKIcE|url-status=live}}</ref> Verstappen's mistake on the first lap allowed Hamilton to take the lead which Verstappen retook during the pit stop phase. Verstappen pitted for a second time from the lead and set after the Mercedes duo, overtaking Hamilton for the lead on lap 52 of 53.<ref>{{Citation|title=How Max Verstappen Fought Back To Beat Lewis Hamilton I 2021 French Grand Prix| date=21 June 2021 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H_Ty1fYKGkQ|access-date=20 January 2022|archive-date=20 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220120011131/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H_Ty1fYKGkQ|url-status=live}}</ref> He also took the fastest lap point, extending his championship lead to twelve points<ref>{{Cite web|title=2021 French Grand Prix race report & highlights: Verstappen triumphs over Hamilton after late pass in scintillating French Grand Prix|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-triumphs-over-hamilton-after-late-pass-in-scintillating-french.22o4zqXsOtjAcFiaBxva2q.html|access-date=29 June 2021|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=21 June 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210621004259/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-triumphs-over-hamilton-after-late-pass-in-scintillating-french.22o4zqXsOtjAcFiaBxva2q.html|url-status=live}}</ref> and achieving the first [[List of Formula One driver records#Pole, win, and fastest lap in same race|hat-trick]] of his career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.french-gp-facts-and-stats-verstappens-first-f1-hat-trick-and-a-special.5RdIdqVagUjxZf5rQ3VASt.html|title=French GP Facts & Stats: Verstappen's first F1 hat-trick, and a special podium for Perez|first=Sean|last=Kelly|date=20 June 2021|publisher=Formula One|access-date=7 July 2022|archive-date=21 June 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210621003951/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.french-gp-facts-and-stats-verstappens-first-f1-hat-trick-and-a-special.5RdIdqVagUjxZf5rQ3VASt.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Verstappen clinched pole position again at the [[2021 Styrian Grand Prix|Styrian Grand Prix]] and led the race from start to finish, to give him his fourth win of the season and further extend his lead to 18 points.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sportstiger.com/max-verstappen-wins-styrian-gp-2021-beats-lewis-hamilton-and-valtteri-bottas-in-austria/ |title=Max Verstappen wins Styrian GP 2021; beats Lewis Hamilton and Valtteri Bottas in Austria |work=SportsTiger |date=27 June 2021 |access-date=27 June 2021 |archive-date=27 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210627144914/https://www.sportstiger.com/max-verstappen-wins-styrian-gp-2021-beats-lewis-hamilton-and-valtteri-bottas-in-austria/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

Verstappen took pole position at the [[2021 Austrian Grand Prix|Austrian Grand Prix]], led every lap from start to finish, set the fastest lap, and won the race for his first career [[grand slam (Formula One)|grand slam]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-waltzes-to-second-win-in-a-row-at-red-bull-ring-as-bottas-beats.31KpLIZDzipY9FhputWqf7.html|title=Verstappen waltzes to second win in a row at Red Bull Ring, as Bottas beats Norris to P2|date=4 July 2021|access-date=19 June 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=30 November 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211130235934/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-waltzes-to-second-win-in-a-row-at-red-bull-ring-as-bottas-beats.31KpLIZDzipY9FhputWqf7.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=4 July 2021|title=F1 – Verstappen extends title lead with Austrian Grand Prix grand slam as Hamilton finishes fourth|url=https://www.fia.com/news/f1-verstappen-extends-title-lead-austrian-grand-prix-grand-slam-hamilton-finishes-fourth|access-date=4 July 2021|website=Federation Internationale de l'Automobile|archive-date=4 July 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210704160816/https://www.fia.com/news/f1-verstappen-extends-title-lead-austrian-grand-prix-grand-slam-hamilton-finishes-fourth|url-status=live}}</ref> being the youngest to do so.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Aggarwal|first=Abhay|date=15 July 2021|title=What Is a Grand Slam in F1?|url=https://www.essentiallysports.com/f1-news-what-is-a-grand-slam-in-f1/|url-status=live|access-date=17 July 2021|website=EssentiallySports|archive-date=17 July 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210717162011/https://www.essentiallysports.com/f1-news-what-is-a-grand-slam-in-f1/}}</ref> With the win, Verstappen also became the first driver to win three races in three consecutive weekends, starting at the French Grand Prix on 20 June, then the Styrian Grand Prix on 27 June and ending with the Austrian Grand Prix on 4 July.<ref>{{Cite web|year=2021|title=Verstappen has little interest in the grand slam: 'As long as we win'|url=https://www.gpblog.com/en/amp/88345/verstappen-has-little-interest-in-the-grand-slam-as-long-as-we-win|url-status=live|access-date=4 July 2021|website=gpblog.com|archive-date=9 July 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210709191340/https://www.gpblog.com/en/amp/88345/verstappen-has-little-interest-in-the-grand-slam-as-long-as-we-win}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=4 July 2021|title=Austrian GP: Post-Race reaction from Max, Perez and Horner|url=https://www.bleachersnews.com/austrian-gp-post-race-reaction-from-max-perez-and-horner/|access-date=4 July 2021|website=Bleachers News|archive-date=9 July 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210709213140/https://www.bleachersnews.com/austrian-gp-post-race-reaction-from-max-perez-and-horner/|url-status=live}}</ref> At the next race; the [[2021 British Grand Prix|British Grand Prix]], Verstappen was involved in a high-speed collision at the ''[[Silverstone Circuit#Circuit|Copse]]'' corner with Hamilton on the first lap. This resulted in a 51 ''[[G-force|g]]'' impact with the barrier.<ref>{{Citation|title=Verstappen & Hamilton Collide at Silverstone {{!}} 2021 British Grand Prix| date=18 July 2021 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oIKel6jVD3Q|access-date=19 January 2022|archive-date=3 July 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220703032242/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oIKel6jVD3Q|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Verstappen's Silverstone crash power unit given the all-clear by Honda after Friday running in Hungary|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappens-silverstone-crash-power-unit-given-the-all-clear-by-honda-after.4gmPYE3cbWVQzNGN1mbYlc.html|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=18 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220118142945/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappens-silverstone-crash-power-unit-given-the-all-clear-by-honda-after.4gmPYE3cbWVQzNGN1mbYlc.html|url-status=live}}</ref> He was taken to the Silverstone circuit's medical centre after the crash and was then taken to Coventry hospital for precautionary checks and further assessment, before eventually being discharged at 22:00 local time on Sunday night.<ref>{{Cite web |date=18 July 2021 |title=British GP: Lewis Hamilton wins dramatic home race after big Max Verstappen crash as title lead is cut |url=https://www.skysports.com/f1/news/12433/12358463/british-gp-lewis-hamilton-wins-dramatic-home-race-after-big-max-verstappen-crash-as-title-lead-is-cut |access-date=18 July 2021 |archive-date=17 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220317051534/https://www.skysports.com/f1/news/12433/12358463/british-gp-lewis-hamilton-wins-dramatic-home-race-after-big-max-verstappen-crash-as-title-lead-is-cut |url-status=live}}</ref> Hamilton would go on to win the race, reducing Verstappen's lead in the championship to eight points.<ref>{{Cite web|title=2021 British Grand Prix race report & highlights: Hamilton overcomes first-lap collision with Verstappen to hunt down Leclerc for 8th British GP win|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.hamilton-overcomes-first-lap-collision-with-verstappen-to-hunt-down-leclerc.AgFOAxlzlpWSTiHS0Hsbe.html|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=18 July 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210718220128/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.hamilton-overcomes-first-lap-collision-with-verstappen-to-hunt-down-leclerc.AgFOAxlzlpWSTiHS0Hsbe.html|url-status=live}}</ref> At the next race, the [[2021 Hungarian Grand Prix|Hungarian Grand Prix]], Verstappen's car suffered damage in a multi-car collision on lap 1, where Mercedes driver Valtteri Bottas was deemed at fault. He ended the race in tenth which was promoted to ninth after Sebastian Vettel was disqualified. The outcome of the race allowed Hamilton to take the lead of the championship.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/f1/news/31381/12370206/hungarian-gp-max-verstappen-red-bull-rue-brutal-valtteri-bottas-triggered-start-chaos-after-lost-title-leads |title=Hungarian GP: Max Verstappen, Red Bull rue 'brutal' Valtteri Bottas-triggered start chaos after lost title leads |last=Galloway |first=James |date=2 August 2021 |website=skysports.com |access-date=4 August 2021 |archive-date=5 August 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210805035034/https://www.skysports.com/f1/news/31381/12370206/hungarian-gp-max-verstappen-red-bull-rue-brutal-valtteri-bottas-triggered-start-chaos-after-lost-title-leads |url-status=live}}</ref>

Following the summer break, Verstappen qualified on pole at the [[2021 Belgian Grand Prix|Belgian Grand Prix]], ahead of Williams driver [[George Russell (racing driver)|George Russell]] in second and Lewis Hamilton in third.<ref>{{Citation|title=Qualifying Highlights {{!}} 2021 Belgian Grand Prix| date=28 August 2021 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E_CvS-dN99Y|access-date=19 January 2022|archive-date=19 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220119002339/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E_CvS-dN99Y|url-status=live}}</ref> The race was run for three laps, all behind the safety car, with the race official race results taken from the running order at the end of the first lap, with Hamilton and Verstappen both retaining their qualifying positions. As less than 75% of the race distance was completed, half points were awarded, resulting in Verstappen closing the gap to Hamilton to three points.<ref>{{cite news |last=Benson |first=Andrew |title=Max Verstappen declared winner of aborted rain-hit Belgian Grand Prix |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/formula1/58377097 |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=29 August 2021 |archive-date=29 August 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210829172106/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/formula1/58377097 |url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[2021 Dutch Grand Prix|Dutch Grand Prix]] Verstappen again qualified on pole, beating Hamilton by 0.038 seconds.<ref>{{cite web|title=Verstappen says technical issues prevented Dutch GP pole lap being even faster around 'incredible' Zandvoort|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-says-technical-issues-prevented-pole-lap-being-even-faster-around.63hSAhZT8QfMy86azal66v.html|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=18 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220118232921/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-says-technical-issues-prevented-pole-lap-being-even-faster-around.63hSAhZT8QfMy86azal66v.html|url-status=live}}</ref> During the race Verstappen was able to fend off attacks from both Mercedes drivers to take the win, taking the lead in the Drivers' Championship by three points.<ref name="RedBull.com">{{cite web |title=Dutch Grand Prix 2021: race report and reaction |website=RedBull.com |date=5 September 2021 |url=https://www.redbull.com/int-en/dutch-f1-grand-prix-2021-race-report |access-date=18 December 2021 |archive-date=18 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211218075510/https://www.redbull.com/int-en/dutch-f1-grand-prix-2021-race-report |url-status=live}}</ref> For the {{F1GP|2021|Russian}}, Verstappen was required to start at the back of the grid for exceeding his quota of power unit components.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Verstappen set to start Russian GP from the back of the grid after engine change|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-set-to-start-russian-gp-from-the-back-of-the-grid-after-engine.7f6jFpCcP8YyCh2A8UEGMw.html|url-status=live|access-date=26 September 2021|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=30 October 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211030080928/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-set-to-start-russian-gp-from-the-back-of-the-grid-after-engine.7f6jFpCcP8YyCh2A8UEGMw.html}}</ref> He made his way back up the field, and after taking an early pit stop for intermediate tyres late in the race, he finished second.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.thecheckeredflag.co.uk/2021/09/max-verstappen-we-made-a-great-decision-with-the-timing-and-took-the-right-lap-to-pit/|title = Max Verstappen: "We made a great decision with the timing and took the right lap to pit"|date = 27 September 2021|access-date = 27 September 2021|archive-date = 27 September 2021|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210927094249/https://www.thecheckeredflag.co.uk/2021/09/max-verstappen-we-made-a-great-decision-with-the-timing-and-took-the-right-lap-to-pit/|url-status = live}}</ref> At the [[2021 Turkish Grand Prix|Turkish Grand Prix]], Verstappen qualified second with Bottas on pole.<ref>{{Cite web|date=9 October 2021|title=Valtteri Bottas gets Turkish F1 GP pole in boost for fastest man Lewis Hamilton|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2021/oct/09/valtteri-bottas-turkish-f1-gp-pole-lewis-hamilton-max-verstappen|access-date=19 January 2022|website=The Guardian|archive-date=9 October 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211009132422/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2021/oct/09/valtteri-bottas-turkish-f1-gp-pole-lewis-hamilton-max-verstappen|url-status=live}}</ref> With the race being run in wet conditions and the drivers on intermediate tyres the whole race, Verstappen finished second behind Bottas, taking the lead in the Drivers' Championship by six points as Hamilton finished fifth.<ref>{{cite web |last=Benson |first=Andrew |title=Turkish Grand Prix: Valtteri Bottas wins as Max Verstappen retakes title lead |publisher=BBC Sport |date=10 October 2021 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/formula1/58863226 |access-date=23 October 2021 |archive-date=22 October 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211022194759/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/formula1/58863226 |url-status=live}}</ref>

[[File:2021_United_States_Grand_Prix_23_(cropped).jpg|thumb|Verstappen battling with Lewis Hamilton for the lead at the 2021 United States Grand Prix]]

At the [[2021 United States Grand Prix|United States Grand Prix]], Verstappen took pole position in qualifying, edging Hamilton by 0.209 seconds.<ref>{{Cite web|title=2021 United States Grand Prix qualifying report and highlights: Verstappen beats Hamilton to pole position with sensational final lap in Austin|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.qualifying-verstappen-pips-hamilton-to-pole-position-with-sensational-final.6zcE50igI0cWw2XVigtY6x.html|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=8 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211208094708/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.qualifying-verstappen-pips-hamilton-to-pole-position-with-sensational-final.6zcE50igI0cWw2XVigtY6x.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Verstappen won the race and extended his lead in the Drivers' Championship to twelve points as Hamilton finished second with the fastest lap.<ref name="BBC Sport 2021">{{cite web |title=Title battle heads into its climax |publisher=BBC Sport |date=25 October 2021 |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/59032201 |access-date=18 December 2021 |archive-date=18 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211218072035/https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/59032201 |url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[2021 Mexico City Grand Prix]], Verstappen qualified third with a gap to pole-sitter Bottas of 0.350 seconds.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mexico City qualifying: Mercedes shock Red Bull as Bottas takes pole ahead of Hamilton|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.qualifying-mercedes-shock-red-bull-as-bottas-takes-pole-ahead-of-hamilton-in.2dTyrMJFp6YU4FliMrIYQ0.html|access-date=19 January 2022|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=5 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211205223654/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.qualifying-mercedes-shock-red-bull-as-bottas-takes-pole-ahead-of-hamilton-in.2dTyrMJFp6YU4FliMrIYQ0.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Verstappen's main rival Hamilton qualified second. At the start, Verstappen took the lead from Bottas and Hamilton into turn 1, and won the race; and as a result extended his lead in the championship to 19 points.<ref name="Fox Sports 2021">{{cite web |title=Hamilton has vowed to 'keep on fighting'. But his F1 crown is finally starting to slip |work=Fox Sports |date=8 November 2021 |url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/motorsport/formula-one/f1-news-mexico-grand-prix-2021-lewis-hamilton-max-verstappen-drivers-championship-standings-next-race-latest/news-story/9d8474f15bb968196e6b29d772b50f4c |access-date=18 December 2021 |archive-date=6 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211206233354/https://www.foxsports.com.au/motorsport/formula-one/f1-news-mexico-grand-prix-2021-lewis-hamilton-max-verstappen-drivers-championship-standings-next-race-latest/news-story/9d8474f15bb968196e6b29d772b50f4c |url-status=live}}</ref>

Verstappen and Hamilton each entered the final round of the championship—the {{F1GP|2021|Abu Dhabi}} at [[Yas Marina Circuit|Yas Marina]]—on exactly 369.5 points, with Verstappen leading on countback.<ref>{{cite web|title=How can Lewis Hamilton win the 2021 F1 title?|url=https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/how-can-lewis-hamilton-win-the-2021-f1-title/6857947/|access-date=12 February 2022|website=Autosport|date=6 December 2021 |archive-date=12 February 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220212104346/https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/how-can-lewis-hamilton-win-the-2021-f1-title/6857947/|url-status=live}}</ref> Verstappen qualified on pole position by nearly four-tenths of a second, but had a slow start and lost the lead to Hamilton into turn one. He attempted to re-pass Hamilton at turn six, who controversially cut the track and maintained the lead without penalty, despite Verstappen and Red Bull's complaints over team radio. Verstappen was trailing Hamilton by over 10 seconds until a safety car was called with five laps remaining, following a crash involving [[Nicholas Latifi]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Race Highlights {{!}} 2021 Abu Dhabi Grand Prix| date=12 December 2021 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7QJ-N-AQJYc|access-date=20 January 2022|archive-date=13 October 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221013203428/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7QJ-N-AQJYc|url-status=live}}</ref> The withdrawal of the safety car and subsequent resumption of the race with one lap remaining was met with further controversy; race director [[Michael Masi]] only allowed a certain number of lapped cars through, saving time to allow the race to be restarted once the track had been cleared. Verstappen passed Hamilton at turn five of the final lap of the race to become the [[Formula One drivers from the Netherlands|first Dutch Formula One World Champion]] and the [[World Drivers' Championship|34th overall]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/formula1/59628024 |title=Max Verstappen wins title after last-lap overtake of Lewis Hamilton, Mercedes protests rejected |publisher=BBC Sport |date=12 December 2021 |access-date=14 December 2021 |archive-date=14 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211214231835/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/formula1/59628024 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://racingnews365.com/how-verstappen-joined-f1s-list-of-world-champions|title=How Verstappen joined F1's list of World Champions|date=12 December 2021 |access-date=13 December 2021|archive-date=13 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211213045157/https://racingnews365.com/how-verstappen-joined-f1s-list-of-world-champions|url-status=live}}</ref> Mercedes protested and stated intention to appeal the race results, arguing all lapped cars should have been allowed to pass under the regulations, but Red Bull counter-argued that this was not specified in the regulations with the word "any" used as opposed to "all".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fia.com/sites/default/files/doc_58_-_2021_abu_dhabi_grand_prix_-_decision_-_mercedes_protest_art._48.12.pdf |title=Decision – Mercedes Protest Art. 48.12 |date=12 December 2021 |publisher=[[Fédération Internationale de l'Automobile]] |access-date=19 December 2021 |archive-date=12 December 2021 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20211212191155/https://www.fia.com/sites/default/files/doc_58_-_2021_abu_dhabi_grand_prix_-_decision_-_mercedes_protest_art._48.12.pdf |url-status=live}}</ref> The protest was subsequently rejected, confirming Verstappen as the World Drivers' Champion, although the FIA amended the wording of the rule in question for the 2022 season onwards.<ref>{{Cite web |date=19 March 2022 |title=2021 F1 Abu Dhabi Grand Prix – Report to the World Motor Sport Council – 19 March 2022 |url=https://www.fia.com/2021-f1-abu-dhabi-grand-prix-report-world-motor-sport-council-19-march-2022 |access-date=25 March 2022 |website=[[Federation Internationale de l'Automobile]] |archive-date=24 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220324224707/https://www.fia.com/2021-f1-abu-dhabi-grand-prix-report-world-motor-sport-council-19-march-2022 |url-status=live}}</ref> Verstappen was named the best driver of the season by ''[[Autosport]]'' and ''The Race'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/ranking-the-top-10-formula-1-drivers-of-2021/6929359/ |title=Ranking the top 10 Formula 1 drivers of 2021 |last=Kalinauckas |first=Alex |date=20 December 2021 |website=[[Autosport]] |publisher=[[Motorsport Network]] |access-date=14 December 2024 |issn=0269-946X |archive-date=2 September 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220902103245/https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/ranking-the-top-10-formula-1-drivers-of-2021/6929359/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.the-race.com/formula-1/top-10-formula-1-drivers-of-2021-our-verdict/ |title=Top 10 Formula 1 drivers of 2021 – Our verdict |last=Beer |first=Matt |date=14 December 2021 |website=The Race |publisher=The Race Media |access-date=14 December 2024 |archive-date=26 May 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240526143840/https://www.the-race.com/formula-1/top-10-formula-1-drivers-of-2021-our-verdict/ |url-status=live }}</ref> whilst also topping official polls of fellow drivers and team principals.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/exclusive-the-top-10-f1-drivers-of-2021-as-chosen-by-the-drivers.6DWHaJ3vf5A3jc7hO9ivkz |title=EXCLUSIVE: The Top 10 F1 drivers of 2021 – as chosen by the drivers |last=Barretto |first=Lawrence |date=28 December 2021 |website=[[Formula 1]] |publisher=[[Formula One Group]] |access-date=14 December 2024 |archive-date=18 May 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240518221918/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/exclusive-the-top-10-f1-drivers-of-2021-as-chosen-by-the-drivers.6DWHaJ3vf5A3jc7hO9ivkz |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/revealed-f1s-team-bosses-choose-their-top-10-drivers-of-2021.1sK8ysV0LK0MIbeNsHAkgY |title=REVEALED: F1’s team bosses choose their Top 10 drivers of 2021 |last=Barretto |first=Lawrence |date=27 December 2021 |website=[[Formula 1]] |publisher=[[Formula One Group]] |access-date=14 December 2024 |archive-date=12 December 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241212123759/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/revealed-f1s-team-bosses-choose-their-top-10-drivers-of-2021.1sK8ysV0LK0MIbeNsHAkgY |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Mark Hughes (journalist)|Mark Hughes]] of ''[[Motor Sport (magazine)|Motor Sport]]'' also ranked Verstappen first, describing his season as a "stunning combination of speed and racecraft, totally fearless, incredible tenacity and ability to comeback from adversity".<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=https://www.motorsportmagazine.com/archive/article/february-2022/78/2021s-top-10-f1-drivers-rated/ |title=2021's top 10 F1 drivers rated |last=Hughes |first=Mark |date=February 2022 |website=[[Motor Sport (magazine)|Motor Sport]] |access-date=14 December 2024 |issn=0027-2019 |archive-date=22 June 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240622004438/https://www.motorsportmagazine.com/archive/article/february-2022/78/2021s-top-10-f1-drivers-rated/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

==== 2022: Dominant second title ====
[[File:RB18 JapaneseGP FP2.jpg|thumb|Verstappen at the [[2022 Japanese Grand Prix]], where he won his second World Drivers' Championship]]
In March 2022, Verstappen signed a five-year contract extension with Red Bull Racing for the 2023 to 2028 seasons.<ref name=":3" /> From this season onward, he would use the number 1 instead of his regular number 33 as the reigning world champion.<ref>{{cite web|date=18 January 2022|title=Why Verstappen plans to use number 1 on his car, but Hamilton decided not to|url=https://racingnews365.com/why-verstappen-will-use-number-1-on-his-car-but-hamilton-didnt|access-date=24 April 2024|publisher=Racingnews365.com|archive-date=24 April 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240424144505/https://racingnews365.com/why-verstappen-will-use-number-1-on-his-car-but-hamilton-didnt|url-status=live}}</ref>

Verstappen retired from second place at the season-opening {{F1 GP|2022|Bahrain}} with a fuel system issue. He won the {{F1 GP|2022|Saudi Arabian}}, having benefited from a pit stop during safety car conditions to pass teammate and pole-sitter Pérez, but suffered another fuel-related retirement from second place at the {{F1 GP|2022|Australian}}. This left him 46 points behind championship leader Charles Leclerc after three races. Verstappen responded by winning the next three races; he achieved sprint victory and a [[grand slam (Formula One)|grand slam]] at the {{F1 GP|2022|Emilia Romagna}},<ref>{{cite web |last=Kelly |first=Sean |date=24 April 2022 |title=Facts and Stats: A grand slam first, and Red Bull's maiden double score at Imola |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.facts-and-stats-a-grand-slam-first-and-red-bulls-maiden-double-score-at.7nAGUuihqzKZA9PoyCUCf6.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220712125614/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.facts-and-stats-a-grand-slam-first-and-red-bulls-maiden-double-score-at.7nAGUuihqzKZA9PoyCUCf6.html |archive-date=12 July 2022 |access-date=7 July 2022 |publisher=Formula One}}</ref> won from third on the grid at the {{F1 GP|2022|Miami}} and gained from Leclerc's retirement at the {{F1 GP|2022|Spanish}} to lead the Drivers' Championship. Further wins came at the {{F1 GP|2022|Azerbaijan}}, where Leclerc again retired, and from pole position at the {{F1 GP|2022|Canadian}}. Verstappen qualified second at the {{F1 GP|2022|British}}, but floor damage from running over debris harmed his pace and resulted in a seventh-place finish.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Verstappen reveals part of floor was 'completely destroyed' by debris after lowly P7 finish at Silverstone|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-reveals-part-of-floor-was-completely-destroyed-by-debris-after.d6CvA4vD6cW9QskPADpst.html|access-date=5 July 2022|website=formula1|archive-date=5 July 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220705143942/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-reveals-part-of-floor-was-completely-destroyed-by-debris-after.d6CvA4vD6cW9QskPADpst.html|url-status=live}}</ref> He took pole position at the {{F1 GP|2022|Austrian}} and won the sprint, but was overtaken by Leclerc in the race and finished second, reducing his championship lead over Leclerc to 38 points.

Following this, Verstappen went on to win five races consecutively. Pole-sitter Leclerc crashed out of the {{F1 GP|2022|French}}, allowing Verstappen to win. Power unit issues meant he qualified tenth for the {{F1 GP|2022|Hungarian}},<ref>{{Cite web |date=30 July 2022 |title=F1: Power unit fault "painful" for Verstappen after surprise pace |url=https://www.racefans.net/2022/07/30/power-unit-fault-painful-for-verstappen-after-cars-pace-surprises/ |access-date=30 July 2022 |website=RaceFans |archive-date=30 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220730212753/https://www.racefans.net/2022/07/30/power-unit-fault-painful-for-verstappen-after-cars-pace-surprises/ |url-status=live}}</ref> but overtakes in the opening laps and pit stop [[Glossary of motorsport terms#U|undercuts]] meant he went on to take victory, despite briefly losing the lead after a spin.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Wood |first=Will |date=31 July 2022 |title=Verstappen spins and wins from 10th on grid as Ferrari pair finish off the podium |url=https://www.racefans.net/2022/07/31/verstappen-spins-wins-from-10th-on-grid-as-ferrari-pair-finish-off-podium/ |access-date=31 July 2022 |website=RaceFans |archive-date=31 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220731231826/https://www.racefans.net/2022/07/31/verstappen-spins-wins-from-10th-on-grid-as-ferrari-pair-finish-off-podium/ |url-status=live}}</ref> He set the fastest qualifying time at the {{F1 GP|2022|Belgian}} but was demoted to 14th on the grid with a power unit components penalty. Despite this, he progressed to the race lead by lap 12 and went on to win.<ref name="belg2022">{{cite web |title=Verstappen cruises to Belgian Grand Prix victory from P14 as Perez completes Red Bull 1–2 |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-cruises-to-belgian-grand-prix-victory-from-p15-as-perez-completes.2J5xxc79o1DGvziQOegt7i.html |publisher=Formula One |access-date=28 August 2022 |archive-date=29 August 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220829080749/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-cruises-to-belgian-grand-prix-victory-from-p15-as-perez-completes.2J5xxc79o1DGvziQOegt7i.html |url-status=live}}</ref> He took pole position and his 30th race victory at his home race, the {{F1 GP|2022|Dutch}}, and then won from seventh on the grid at the {{F1 GP|2022|Italian}}.

Verstappen's winning streak was ended at the {{F1 GP|2022|Singapore}}. He ran out of fuel in qualifying and started the race eighth.<ref>{{Cite web |date=1 October 2022 |title=Leclerc claims pole position by 0.022s from Perez in stunning wet-dry Singapore qualifying as Verstappen takes P8 |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.leclerc-claims-pole-position-by-0-022s-from-perez-in-stunning-wet-dry.1VYcL6oJ34e4vHUpdJtDca.html |access-date=3 October 2022 |publisher=Formula One |archive-date=8 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230608120702/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.leclerc-claims-pole-position-by-0-022s-from-perez-in-stunning-wet-dry.1VYcL6oJ34e4vHUpdJtDca.html |url-status=live}}</ref> He lost places at the start and later had to make an extra pit stop due to a tyre lock-up, finishing seventh. Victory from pole at the shortened {{F1 GP|2022|Japanese}} gave him a 113-point lead in the standings with four races remaining, securing him his second World Drivers' Championship.<ref name="Morlidge 2022">{{cite web |last=Morlidge |first=Matt |title=Max Verstappen crowned 2022 F1 world champion amid Japanese GP confusion after winning wet race |publisher=Sky Sports |date=9 October 2022 |url=https://www.skysports.com/f1/news/12433/12707671/max-verstappen-crowned-2022-f1-world-champion-amid-japanese-gp-confusion-after-winning-wet-race |access-date=9 October 2022 |archive-date=9 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221009090638/https://www.skysports.com/f1/news/12433/12707671/max-verstappen-crowned-2022-f1-world-champion-amid-japanese-gp-confusion-after-winning-wet-race |url-status=live}}</ref> He won the next two races, the [[2022 United States Grand Prix|United States]] and [[2022 Mexico City Grand Prix|Mexico City]] Grands Prix, finished sixth at the {{F1 GP|2022|São Paulo}} after a collision with Lewis Hamilton, and won the season-ending {{F1 GP|2022|Abu Dhabi}} from pole.

Abu Dhabi was his fifteenth victory of the year, breaking the record of thirteen race wins in a season shared by Michael Schumacher in {{F1|2004}} and Sebastian Vettel in {{F1|2013}}. He won the championship with 454 points, beating Lewis Hamilton's {{F1|2019}} record of 413.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/max-by-numbers-the-incredible-stats-behind-verstappens-2022-championship.5CEqUJDvM2QHafTv0Zs63q|title=MAX BY NUMBERS: The amazing stats behind Verstappen's 2022 title winning campaign|publisher=Formula One|first=Nadim|last=Bart-Williams|date=25 November 2022|access-date=31 March 2024|archive-date=31 March 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240331134653/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/max-by-numbers-the-incredible-stats-behind-verstappens-2022-championship.5CEqUJDvM2QHafTv0Zs63q|url-status=live}}</ref>

====2023: Record-breaking third title====
[[File:FIA F1 Austria 2023 Race (1).jpg|thumb|left|Verstappen leading the race at the [[2023 Austrian Grand Prix]]]]
Verstappen remained with Red Bull alongside Sergio Pérez for the 2023 season. His season began with a win from pole at the {{F1 GP|2023|Bahrain}}. A driveshaft failure in qualifying at the {{F1 GP|2023|Saudi Arabian}} resulted in a 15th-place start, but he gained positions in the race to finish second behind Pérez.<ref>{{cite web |last=Boxall-Legge |first=Jake |date=18 March 2023 |title=F1 Saudi Arabian GP: Perez grabs pole as Verstappen hits trouble |url=https://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/f1-saudi-arabian-gp-perez-grabs-pole-as-verstappen-hits-trouble/10445464/ |access-date=20 March 2023 |website=Motorsport.com |archive-date=20 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230320210723/https://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/f1-saudi-arabian-gp-perez-grabs-pole-as-verstappen-hits-trouble/10445464/ |url-status=live}}</ref> He again won from pole at the {{F1 GP|2023|Australian}} despite losing positions to the Mercedes drivers during the race,<ref name="Sky Sports - wild finish">{{cite web |last=Johnston |first=Sam |date=2 April 2023 |title=Australian GP: Max Verstappen holds off Lewis Hamilton for victory after wild finish to chaotic race |url=https://www.skysports.com/f1/news/12433/12847996/australian-gp-max-verstappen-holds-off-lewis-hamilton-for-victory-after-wild-finish-to-chaotic-race |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230409110829/https://www.skysports.com/f1/news/12433/12847996/australian-gp-max-verstappen-holds-off-lewis-hamilton-for-victory-after-wild-finish-to-chaotic-race |archive-date=9 April 2023 |access-date=2 April 2023 |publisher=Sky Sports F1}}</ref> but finished second to Pérez, who made a safety car pit stop, at the {{F1 GP|2023|Azerbaijan}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/f1-azerbaijan-gp-perez-leads-dominant-red-bull-1-2-from-leclerc/10463146/|title=F1 Azerbaijan GP: Perez leads dominant Red Bull 1–2 from Leclerc|last=Boxall-Legge|first=Jake|website=Autosport|date=30 April 2023|access-date=30 April 2023|archive-date=30 April 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230430222636/https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/f1-azerbaijan-gp-perez-leads-dominant-red-bull-1-2-from-leclerc/10463146/|url-status=live}}</ref>

After this began Verstappen's record-breaking win streak. He started ninth at the {{F1 GP|2023|Miami}} as [[Racing flags#Red flag|red flags]] in qualifying aborted his lap but passed the drivers ahead including pole-sitter Pérez to win. The next four races, the [[2023 Monaco Grand Prix|Monaco]], [[2023 Spanish Grand Prix|Spanish]], [[2023 Canadian Grand Prix|Canadian]] and [[2023 Austrian Grand Prix|Austrian]] Grands Prix, were won comfortably from pole position by Verstappen, including Red Bull's 100th victory in Canada<ref>{{cite web |last=Boxall-Legge |first=Jake |date=18 June 2023 |title=F1 Canadian GP: Verstappen clinches Red Bull's 100th F1 win |url=https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/f1-canadian-gp-race-report/10484848/ |website=Autosport |access-date=19 June 2023 |archive-date=19 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230619103008/https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/f1-canadian-gp-race-report/10484848/ |url-status=live}}</ref> and a sprint win in Austria. He took pole at the {{F1 GP|2023|British}} but briefly lost the lead to [[Lando Norris]] at the start before regaining the position to win. He qualified 0.003 seconds behind Lewis Hamilton at the {{F1 GP|2023|Hungarian}}, but overtook him at the first corner and went on to take victory. He claimed pole and the win in the {{F1 GP|2023|Belgian}} sprint and set the fastest qualifying time, but started the race sixth due to an engine component penalty. He went on to overtake Pérez to win the race. He won from pole at the rain-affected {{F1 GP|2023|Dutch}} and was victorious again at the {{F1 GP|2023|Italian}} despite qualifying behind Carlos Sainz Jr. This victory marked his tenth consecutive win, breaking Sebastian Vettel's record of nine from 2013,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Saunders |first=Nate |date=3 September 2023 |title=Verstappen claims record 10th straight F1 win in Italy |url=https://www.espn.com/f1/story/_/id/38319156/max-verstappen-claims-record-10th-straight-f1-win-italian-grand-prix |access-date=3 September 2023 |website=ESPN.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230903144505/https://www.espn.com/f1/story/_/id/38319156/max-verstappen-claims-record-10th-straight-f1-win-italian-grand-prix |archive-date=3 September 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-charges-to-monza-victory-for-record-breaking-10th-successive-f1.6jCUOTZ4lZB3kxfIiwsiHK.html |title=Verstappen charges to Monza victory for record-breaking 10th successive F1 win |date=3 September 2023 |website=Formula One |author=Formula One Management |access-date=21 September 2023 |archive-date=3 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230903164334/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-charges-to-monza-victory-for-record-breaking-10th-successive-f1.6jCUOTZ4lZB3kxfIiwsiHK.html |url-status=live}}</ref> and Red Bull's fifteenth consecutive win, a record previously held by [[McLaren]] with eleven in {{F1|1988}}. It also marked the first time a driver had completed a perfect European season in Formula One history.

Both Red Bulls were eliminated in Q2 at the {{F1 GP|2023|Singapore}} and were unable to make an impression in the race, with Verstappen and Pérez finishing fifth and eighth respectively, ending the winning streak.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Sainz takes sensational Singapore Grand Prix victory |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.sainz-holds-off-norris-and-fast-charging-mercedes-pair-to-take-sensational.16sNsRUz2MAFyXxSE3RdwX.html |access-date=18 September 2023 |publisher=Formula One |archive-date=17 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230917160814/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.sainz-holds-off-norris-and-fast-charging-mercedes-pair-to-take-sensational.16sNsRUz2MAFyXxSE3RdwX.html |url-status=live}}</ref> This would be the only break in Verstappen's success, as he went on to win the remaining seven races of the season. His victory from pole at the {{F1 GP|2023|Japanese}} gave Red Bull their sixth Constructors' Championship title.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Richards |first=Giles |date=24 September 2023 |title=Max Verstappen on verge of F1 world title after winning Japanese Grand Prix |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2023/sep/24/max-verstappen-on-brink-of-f1-world-title-after-winning-japanese-grand-prix |access-date=25 September 2023 |issn=0261-3077 |archive-date=26 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230926114547/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2023/sep/24/max-verstappen-on-brink-of-f1-world-title-after-winning-japanese-grand-prix |url-status=live}}</ref> He clinched his third World Drivers' Championship title at the {{F1 GP|2023|Qatar}} sprint despite finishing second to [[Oscar Piastri]],<ref>{{Cite web |date=7 October 2023 |title=Verstappen secures third F1 world title as Piastri takes Sprint victory in Qatar |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-secures-third-f1-world-title-as-piastri-takes-sprint-victory-in.4d0SLopnXU9W8uzefnJmu3.html |access-date=8 October 2023 |publisher=Formula One |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231011012612/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-secures-third-f1-world-title-as-piastri-takes-sprint-victory-in.4d0SLopnXU9W8uzefnJmu3.html |archive-date=11 October 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref> then won the race from pole. He won the {{F1 GP|2023|United States}} despite having started sixth due to a lap time deletion in qualifying. He qualified behind both Ferraris at the {{F1 GP|2023|Mexico City}} but passed both drivers to claim the win. He took pole and victory at the {{F1 GP|2023|São Paulo}} and won the sprint having overtook pole-sitter [[Lando Norris]] at the first turn. He started behind Charles Leclerc at the {{F1 GP|2023|Las Vegas}} and received a penalty for forcing him off the track, but Verstappen reclaimed the lead to win.

His pole and victory at the season-ending {{F1 GP|2023|Abu Dhabi}} was his nineteenth win of the year, breaking his own record of fifteen from 2022. He scored 575 points, more than double that of second-placed Pérez and beating his own points-scoring record from 2022.

====2024: Fourth title amid struggles at Red Bull====
[[File:FIA F1 Austria 2024 Nr. 1 Verstappen.jpg|thumb|right|Verstappen (pictured during the {{F1GP|2024|Austrian}}) won seven of the opening 10 rounds in 2024.]]
Verstappen began the {{F1|2024}} season with his fifth career grand slam at the {{F1 GP|2024|Bahrain}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://racer.com/2024/03/02/verstappen-reigns-supreme-in-bahrain-gp/|title=Verstappen reigns supreme in Bahrain GP|website=racer.com|first=Michael|last=Lamonato|date=2 March 2024|access-date=6 May 2024}}</ref> and followed this with another pole and victory at the {{F1 GP|2024|Saudi Arabian}}, his 100th Formula One podium.<ref>{{cite web |title='It's 88 missed podiums!' – Verstappen reflects on 100th F1 rostrum appearance as he praises 'fantastic' Bearman |date=9 March 2024 |work=[[Formula One Management]] |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.its-88-missed-podiums-verstappen-reflects-on-100th-f1-rostrum-appearance-as.4WpkyUZDh8agq8FasXlNdK.html |access-date=6 May 2024 |archive-date=9 March 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240309222336/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.its-88-missed-podiums-verstappen-reflects-on-100th-f1-rostrum-appearance-as.4WpkyUZDh8agq8FasXlNdK.html |url-status=live }}</ref> He took pole again at the {{F1 GP|2024|Australian}} but retired on lap 4, his first retirement since the [[2022 Australian Grand Prix|2022 edition of the race]], with a brake fire, ending his nine-race winning streak and 43 race-finishing streak.<ref name="race-report">{{cite web |title=Sainz storms to victory amid drama in Australia |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/sainz-storms-to-victory-amid-drama-in-australia-as-verstappen-retires-and.4ZVm82EhKLMcVIHurBPr8N |publisher=Formula One |access-date=24 March 2024 |date=24 March 2024 |archive-date=24 March 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240324063853/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/sainz-storms-to-victory-amid-drama-in-australia-as-verstappen-retires-and.4ZVm82EhKLMcVIHurBPr8N |url-status=live}}</ref> This was followed by a pole and win at the {{F1 GP|2024|Japanese}}.<ref>{{cite web |title=Verstappen leads home Perez for Red Bull one-two at Japanese GP after early drama |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/verstappen-leads-home-perez-for-red-bull-one-two-at-japanese-gp-after-early.1rtPVvnBYJgZIEppNtk6ZD |publisher=Formula One |access-date=7 April 2024 |date=7 April 2024 |archive-date=7 April 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240407092737/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/verstappen-leads-home-perez-for-red-bull-one-two-at-japanese-gp-after-early.1rtPVvnBYJgZIEppNtk6ZD |url-status=live}}</ref> He won the sprint at the {{F1 GP|2024|Chinese}} after starting fourth,<ref>{{cite web |title=Verstappen beats Hamilton in dramatic Shanghai Sprint |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/verstappen-charges-to-victory-over-hamilton-in-dramatic-shanghai-sprint.6B8IBGCczrPy6jLU3ztepf |publisher=Formula One |access-date=21 April 2024 |date=20 April 2024 |archive-date=20 April 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240420143726/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/verstappen-charges-to-victory-over-hamilton-in-dramatic-shanghai-sprint.6B8IBGCczrPy6jLU3ztepf |url-status=live}}</ref> then claimed pole and victory in the race.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/verstappen-charges-to-victory-over-norris-and-perez-in-action-packed-chinese.3Uz5CwNh5tEQt62umIGhob |title=Verstappen charges to victory over Norris and Perez in action-packed Chinese GP |date=21 April 2024 |access-date=22 April 2024 |website=Formula One |archive-date=21 April 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240421124322/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/verstappen-charges-to-victory-over-norris-and-perez-in-action-packed-chinese.3Uz5CwNh5tEQt62umIGhob |url-status=live }}</ref> He took another sprint win at the {{F1 GP|2024|Miami}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/verstappen-charges-to-sprint-race-win-over-leclerc-and-perez-in-miami.3ziV5jwPsEc5HCQ1ODdIUF |title=Verstappen charges to Sprint win over Leclerc and Perez in Miami |date=4 May 2024 |access-date=5 May 2024 |website=Formula One}}</ref> and started on pole position, but lost the lead to Lando Norris during the pit stops and was unable to reclaim the place, finishing the race second.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/norris-beats-verstappen-for-breakthrough-maiden-f1-victory-in-action-packed.7f9W6X9L3kPQILyO3NljL1 |title=Norris beats Verstappen for breakthrough maiden F1 victory in action-packed Miami Grand Prix |date=5 May 2024 |access-date=6 May 2024 |website=Formula One |archive-date=13 May 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240513225014/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/norris-beats-verstappen-for-breakthrough-maiden-f1-victory-in-action-packed.7f9W6X9L3kPQILyO3NljL1 |url-status=live}}</ref> He matched [[Ayrton Senna]]'s record of eight consecutive poles at the {{F1 GP|2024|Emilia Romagna}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/formula1/articles/c8vvpq703geo|title=Very special to equal Senna pole record – Verstappen|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Andrew|last=Benson|date=18 May 2024|access-date=18 May 2024|archive-date=18 May 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240518190928/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/formula1/articles/c8vvpq703geo|url-status=live}}</ref> and converted this into his fifth victory of the season. His pole streak ended at the {{F1 GP|2024|Monaco}} where he qualified and finished sixth; Verstappen commented that his [[Red Bull RB20|RB20]] was losing time to its rivals in low-speed corners.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/verstappen-pinpoints-issue-that-cost-him-a-lot-of-lap-time-in-monaco.2UIL0fxvgaAIHuG1SQIvcC|title=Verstappen pinpoints issue that cost him 'a lot of lap time' in Monaco qualifying as pole run comes to an end|publisher=Formula One|date=25 May 2024|access-date=28 May 2024}}</ref>

Verstappen and George Russell set identical lap times in qualifying at the {{F1 GP|2024|Canadian}}, but Russell started on pole position as he had set the lap time first.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/ive-missed-this-feeling-russell-hails-mercedes-progress-after-canada-pole-as.3FNoF51rSbAhHwUKUjTn2u|title='I've missed this feeling!' – Russell hails Mercedes progress after Canada pole as he vows to 'go for it' on race day|website=formula1.com|date=8 June 2024|access-date=9 June 2024|archive-date=9 June 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240609165448/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/ive-missed-this-feeling-russell-hails-mercedes-progress-after-canada-pole-as.3FNoF51rSbAhHwUKUjTn2u|url-status=live}}</ref> Both drivers were overtaken by Norris, but Verstappen later passed Russell then gained the lead from Norris during the pit stops to claim his 60th race win.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/verstappen-beats-norris-to-victory-in-thrilling-wet-dry-canadian-gp.6ytkbh7iDTWC3pJBwiaboI|title=Verstappen beats Norris to victory in thrilling wet/dry Canadian GP|website=formula1.com|date=9 June 2024|access-date=10 June 2024|archive-date=9 June 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240609235243/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/verstappen-beats-norris-to-victory-in-thrilling-wet-dry-canadian-gp.6ytkbh7iDTWC3pJBwiaboI|url-status=live}}</ref> He qualified second behind Norris at the {{F1 GP|2024|Spanish}} but passed him at the start and then overtook Russell to win for the seventh time in 2024.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/verstappen-holds-of-norris-challenge-to-seal-victory-at-the-spanish-grand.7a5UhXMAtkhbslSDNiPVes|title=Verstappen just holds off Norris to win super-tight Spanish Grand Prix as Hamilton claims first podium of 2024|website=formula1.com|date=23 June 2024|access-date=23 June 2024|archive-date=15 July 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240715020622/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/verstappen-holds-of-norris-challenge-to-seal-victory-at-the-spanish-grand.7a5UhXMAtkhbslSDNiPVes|url-status=live}}</ref> Verstappen won the sprint from pole at the {{F1 GP|2024|Austrian}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/verstappen-beats-piastri-and-norris-to-victory-after-epic-austria-sprint.okkV70ksnFFlGE8bmvGId|title=Verstappen beats Piastri and Norris to victory after epic Austria Sprint battle|website=formula1.com|date=29 June 2024|access-date=21 July 2024|archive-date=15 July 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240715020804/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/verstappen-beats-piastri-and-norris-to-victory-after-epic-austria-sprint.okkV70ksnFFlGE8bmvGId|url-status=live}}</ref> and then qualified fastest for the main race.<ref>{{cite web |date=29 June 2024 |title=Formula 1 Qatar Airways Austrian Grand Prix 2024 – Qualifying |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/results.html/2024/races/1239/austria/qualifying.html |access-date=29 June 2024 |publisher=Formula One |archive-date=29 June 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240629154701/https://www.formula1.com/en/results.html/2024/races/1239/austria/qualifying.html |url-status=live}}</ref> He led most of the race but was challenged by Norris in the closing laps before the two drivers collided; Verstappen was handed a time penalty for causing the collision and finished the race fifth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/russell-claims-surprise-win-in-austria-after-verstappen-and-norris.2Kmxvn4a42JYDFhvklagYk|title=Russell claims surprise win in Austria after Verstappen and Norris dramatically collide in battle for the lead|website=www.formula1.com|access-date=4 July 2024|archive-date=15 July 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240715020740/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/russell-claims-surprise-win-in-austria-after-verstappen-and-norris.2Kmxvn4a42JYDFhvklagYk|url-status=live}}</ref> He later commented that the crash did not affect his close friendship with Norris.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/im-not-there-to-crash-you-out-verstappen-shares-details-of-post-austria-chat.4rRZCOwj7apVXWktQlD6fr|title='I'm not there to crash you out' – Verstappen shares details of post-Austria chat with Norris after 'silly' coming together|website=Formula One official website|access-date=7 July 2024|archive-date=6 July 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240706192607/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/im-not-there-to-crash-you-out-verstappen-shares-details-of-post-austria-chat.4rRZCOwj7apVXWktQlD6fr|url-status=live}}</ref> He qualified fourth at the {{F1 GP|2024|British}} and passed Norris in the closing laps to finish second behind Lewis Hamilton.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/f1/news/12433/13174568/british-gp-lewis-hamilton-holds-off-max-verstappen-to-claim-record-ninth-victory-at-silverstone|title=British GP: Lewis Hamilton holds off Max Verstappen to claim record ninth victory at Silverstone|website=skysports.com|date=7 July 2024|access-date=21 July 2024|archive-date=15 July 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240715162017/https://www.skysports.com/f1/news/12433/13174568/british-gp-lewis-hamilton-holds-off-max-verstappen-to-claim-record-ninth-victory-at-silverstone|url-status=live}}</ref> He started third at the {{F1 GP|2024|Hungarian}} but collided with Hamilton and went on to finish fifth. He criticised his team's race strategy and suggested that the RB20 was now behind the race-winning [[McLaren MCL38]] on pace.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/i-want-things-to-be-done-better-fumes-verstappen-after-hungarian-gp-as-he.4FBWinVnmuhICOvt8rIg6c|title='I want things to be done better' fumes Verstappen after Hungarian GP as he admits Red Bull now behind McLaren|website=formula1.com|date=21 July 2024|access-date=21 July 2024|archive-date=22 July 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240722223931/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/i-want-things-to-be-done-better-fumes-verstappen-after-hungarian-gp-as-he.4FBWinVnmuhICOvt8rIg6c|url-status=live}}</ref> Verstappen qualified fastest at the {{F1 GP|2024|Belgian}} but started outside the top ten due to an engine component penalty.<ref>{{cite web|date=26 July 2024|title=Formula 1 Rolex Belgian Grand Prix 2024 – Starting Grid|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/results.html/2024/races/1242/belgium/starting-grid.html|access-date=26 July 2024|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=20 July 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240720125208/https://www.formula1.com/en/results.html/2024/races/1242/belgium/starting-grid.html|url-status=live}}</ref> He recovered positions and was classified fourth in the race,<ref>{{cite web|date=28 July 2024|title=Formula 1 Rolex Belgian Grand Prix 2024 – Race Result|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/results.html/2024/races/1242/belgium/race-result.html|access-date=28 July 2024|publisher=Formula One|archive-date=16 June 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240616005227/https://www.formula1.com/en/results.html/2024/races/1242/belgium/race-result.html|url-status=live}}</ref> extending his lead in the championship to 78 points over Norris going into the summer break.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.statsf1.com/en/2024/belgique/championnat.aspx|title=Belgium 2024 – Championship|website=Stats F1|date=21 July 2024|access-date=28 July 2024|archive-date=2 August 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240802082453/https://www.statsf1.com/en/2024/belgique/championnat.aspx|url-status=live}}</ref>

{{Multiple images
| perrow            = 2
| total_width       = 350
| align             = left
